<HEADLINE> Cohen Says Unable to Confirm Report on Russian-Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Thursday that he could not confirm whether
Russia had negotiated to sell Iraq highly-sensitive dual-use
technology that could be used to produce biological weapons, but
he said it would be up to the United Nations to investigate the
allegation made by the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post published a report on Thursday that a U.N.
inspection team had seized a confidential document back in the
fall that signaled a contract between Russia and Iraq in 1995 for
Russia to sell that weapons equipment.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with NBS, Cohen said: "I don't have any basis
to either confirm or contradict that particular story."
</P>
<P>
But he also told ABC in another interview that the United
Nations should make an investigation to find whether there is any
evidence for that allegation.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have any means of verifying that. That's something
that the U.N. will have to determine, and hopefully the Russian
authorities will be very forthcoming on this issue," he told ABC.
</P>
<P>
Russia dismissed on Thursday the Washington Post's report as
crude inventions.
</P>
<P>
"We decisively deny these crude inventions," Russia's Foreign
Ministry said. "Russia has never made any deals with Iraq that
would violate international sanctions, moreover deals involving
supplies of banned technologies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
