<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Edge Little Higher in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. retail sales edged
a 0.1 percent increase in January, the Commerce Department
reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increase, to a seasonally adjusted 214.8 billion U.S.
dollars, followed a moderate 0.3 percent gain in December and a
tiny 0.1 percent advance in November.
</P>
<P>
In January, discounts drew shoppers back to department stores,
where sales rose 1.6 percent, the biggest gain in last 13 months.
Clothing shops posted a 0.7 percent increase, the best in five
months. But auto sales dropped 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile auto category, sales rose 0.5 percent in
January after declining 0.1 percent in both December and November.
It was the best showing since last July.
</P>
<P>
Also boosting the January advance were sales at building supply
and hardware stores, up 1 percent; furniture stores, up 0.3
percent; restaurants and bars, up 0.9 percent; and drug stores, up
0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, sales fell 0.4 percent at grocery stores and, held
back by declining gasoline prices, 1.3 percent at service
stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
