<HEADLINE> Senior ECA Official Calls for Promotion of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
U.N.Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) said today that ECA has
been fully aware of the importance of the informal sector in
providing the majority of the population with employment and
income, as well as goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting with the theme of ''Promotion of
the Informal Sector for Development in Africa'' held at Africa
Hall here, Lalla Ben Barka, Deputy Executive Secretary of the
ECA, noted that in the last few years quite a number of African
governments have made serious efforts to review policies and to
reformulate strategies in favour of the informal sector.
</P>
<P>
Barka said: ''Promotion of the informal sector for development
in Africa'' is one of two pilot projects ECA has embarked upon as
practical demonstrations of the human-centered approaches to
development.
</P>
<P>
She said that promotion of the informal sector for development
in Africa has been implemented in Ghana and Cote d'Ivoire in the
project's first phase in 1992 to 1993, and in Ethiopia and Zambia
in its second phase from 1996 to April 1998.
</P>
<P>
She said that ECA, together with the International Labour
Organization, has been the lead agencies for the United Nations
Inter-agency Task Force on Poverty Reduction in Africa through
the promotion of the informal sector and employment generating
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her belief that the present gathering between
the diverse expertise coming from different countries and
institutions will result in high-level decisions regarding
follow-up action plans and cooperation agreements in favour of
the micro and small enterprise sector on Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy ECA official, the informal sector
consists mainly of micro and small scale enterprises -- most of
them are self-employed individuals who operate from a
semi-permanent location or site, usually with small
capitalization and without legislated standards of quality.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey of the informal sector operators conducted by
the Central Statistics Authority of Ethiopia in 48 towns in May
1997 shows that there are 584,913 informal sector operators
engaging about 731,000 labour force, eight times larger than
those engaged in the medium and large scale establishments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
