<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Economic Consultative Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government and
the private sector went into consultations on Thursday to find
cures for the ailing economy in the second meeting of the
National Economic Consultative Forum (NECF).
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the executive core group of the NECF, also
attended by President Robert Mugabe, was a follow-up to one last
month which focused on the country's pricing system and how it
could be improved to achieve socio-economic stability.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists at the end of the three-and-half hour
meeting, Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira said
the government would seriously consider the views and comments of
the private sector on improving the macro-economic environment.
</P>
<P>
"The government feels that the macro-economic environment must
be strengthened and that measures are being taken to strengthen
the Zimbabwean Dollar including strengthening of the export
drive," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries
felt very strongly about the need to increase export incentives.
"That will help a lot of industries to keep going," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The government had also been sensitized on the need to reduce
the budget deficit currently standing at 10 percent of gross
domestic product and to privatize loss making parastatals.
</P>
<P>
The previous meeting noted the need to look at the "price of
money" and what could be done to curb the high price increases.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, which was last month rocked by violent riots against
sharp price hikes of basic commodities, is struggling to tackle
the problem of interest rates pegged at around 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The interest rates are not expected to fall in the short term
because of serious inflationary pressure emanating escalating
prices of basic commodities, a fast depreciating currency and an
expected fuel price hike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
