<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi FM: Sensitive Sites Off-limits to Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said here Thursday that Iraq will not put
its ministries and other sensitive sites under international
inspection.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the Arab League here, the Iraqi
minister tried to clarify the eight presidential sites Baghdad has
promised to open to a new international arms inspection team.
</P>
<P>
"By eight presidential sites, we mean eight compounds, but not
villas and palaces. Because if you count these villas and palaces
in the compounds, their number can be more than 60," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that these would exclude such sensitive sites
as ministries and Republican Guard headquarters which the
U.N. Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraqi weapons of
mass destruction (UNSCOM) wants to see.
</P>
<P>
"They are part of our sovereignty," he said, adding that these
sites were not included in the former agreements between the
UNSCOM and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with AL Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid earlier in the day, al-Sahhaf told reporters that Iraq
has been "very objective and practical" since the very beginning
of the "fabricated crisis."
</P>
<P>
The standoff between Iraq and the United States was triggered
off by Iraqi former refusal of full access to U.N. arms inspectors
the presidential sites suspected of hiding weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said Iraq has supported the Russian initiative that
calls for the formation of a special team to carry out the
inspection mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the team will be a "large one," composed of an equal
number of experts from the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council as well as an equal number of experts from
the UNSCOM's 21 member countries.
</P>
<P>
They will inspect all the sites "without any condition" and
with the technical ways and means of verification to verify the
U.S. accusations that Iraq is hiding some prohibited weapons of
mass destruction on those sites, he said.
</P>
<P>
After 60 days, the team should submit a report to the Security
Council and the U.N secretary general, Sahhaf added.
</P>
<P>
"After they prove we are clean, this file should be closed once
and forever. This is the major step and there is nothing else
behind it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care whether this is enough for the Americans or not,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi top diplomat Wednesday met with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
He is on a regional tour to drum up support for averting an
imminent U.S. military strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
