<HEADLINE> Freed Polish Hostages Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Five Polish aid workers held
hostage by Chechen kidnappers two months ago flew home Thursday
morning, a report of the Polish Press Agency said.
</P>
<P>
When meeting the five workers, Polish Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek said his government is always ready to help Poles abroad.
</P>
<P>
The five were abducted on December 17 while delivering
humanitarian aid materials to a village in the Northern Caucasus
republic. They were freed by Chechen security forces on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A report of the central television station said the Polish
police identified one of the five freed hostages as an economic
crime suspect. He probably will be taken into custody soon.
