<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Tourism Expo'98 Opens in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's premier tourism
showcase, Travel Expo'98, opened here Thursday with an investment
conference to discuss appropriate policy and institutional
framework for the development of the sector.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the conference agreed that tourism was one of
the fastest growing sectors in the world which could be used to
create employment and wealth for local communities.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, the industry's performance in the past 10 years
has been commendable, generating 80 million U.S. Dollars in 1995,
140 million U.S. Dollars in 1996 and 200 million U.S. Dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Receipts as a percentage of gross domestic product grew from
2.6 percent in 1990 to 4.6 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Opening the one-day conference, Minsiter for Mines,
Environment and Tourism Simon Moyo said in view of this growth,
it was imperative to increase the level of investment into the
industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the government considered the development of tourism
as a priority and integral part of its overall economic
development strategy.
</P>
<P>
"Statistics indicate that this sector is fast becoming a
strategic growth sector in the economy with vast potential for
the creation of wealth so as to improve the quality of life of
our people and provide a solid foundation for peace and
prosperity," Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
The government, he added, was studying proposals on investment
incentives for tourism prepared jointly by the country's tourism
promotion bodies, the Zimbabwe Tourism Authority and the Zimbabwe
Council for Tourism with the Zimbabwe Investment Center.
</P>
<P>
He said that plans to establish a revolving tourism fund to
help new entrants with start up capital were at an advanced
stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
