<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Executive Mandated for Maritime Transport Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
decided to approve two negotiating mandates authorizing its
executive body, the European Commission, to open talks for
agreements on maritime transport between the EU and China and
India respectively.
</P>
<P>
European Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock Thursday welcomed
the decision taken by the European Council of Ministers, noting
that China is one of the fastest growing markets in the world
while India offers substantial trading potentials.
</P>
<P>
"Effective maritime transport links to and from these countries
are indispensable for developing our trade relations and EU
shipowners have played an essential part in developing them," the
Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive said that agreements in this regard should put
the shipping activities of some of the world's biggest companies
in China, India and the EU on a sound footing.
</P>
<P>
It added they should create a regulatory framework which was
clear, unequivocal and balanced, allowing the economies of the
countries concerned to draw full benefit from the shipping
industry's expertise.
</P>
<P>
The mandate will tackle issues such as the freedom to provide
international maritime transport services, free and
non-discriminatory use of ancillary services, consignors' freedom
of choice with regard to conditions of carriage and treatment of
vessels and trans-shipment in ports.
</P>
<P>
"The agreements should furthermore create a level playing field
for all operators on the parties' territories," the Commission
said.
</P>
<P>
However, it also noted that whereas Chinese and Indian shipping
companies enjoyed a maximum of commercial freedom in the EU,
shipping companies from the EU still encountered a number of
problems in China and India.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the EU member states have given the
Commission a mandate to negotiate on their behalf maritime
agreements with third countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
