<HEADLINE> Estonia Identifies Foreign Policy Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Estonian Foreign Minister
Toomas Ilves on Thursday identified joining the European Union
(EU) as one of the country's foreign policy priorities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, said an Interfax news agency report reaching here
from the Estonian capital of Tallinn, Ilves vowed to "pursue a
security policy in the context of rapprochement with NATO."
</P>
<P>
In his statement made to a parliament hearing, the foreign
minister emphasized that the government will make efforts this
year to acquire a full-fledged NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
Every practical step to strengthen Estonia's defense force
should be taken to lead the country into the Western military
alliance, he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
On relations with Russia, Ilves said they were undoubtedly
better than the same period of last year, adding that "Estonia
should treat Russia as a normal friendly Western nation."
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed regret that relations between the two
countries still lack a sufficient legal foundation.
</P>
<P>
There is no agreement between the two countries on the
protection of investments, on the prevention of dual taxation and
about most favored nation trade status, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has no political will to sign a treaty on its border
with Estonia, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
