<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Women Perform Better in Education Than Men: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Women in the 15 European
Union (EU) member states now achieve more than the opposite sex in
key areas of education but still lag in the race for jobs, it was
learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Women were in the minority in higher education in every EU
member state 20 years ago, but the average is now 103 women to
every 100 men, according to a report published Thursday by
Eurostat, the EU's statistical office based in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Women outnumber men in this field in over half the European
countries. Bulgaria, Iceland and Portugal boast the highest ratio.
</P>
<P>
However, in Germany there are still only 77 women to every 100
men, with 89 in the Netherlands and 92 in Austria.
</P>
<P>
Across the EU, 110 women for every 100 men have higher
education qualifications. The female ratio is higher everywhere
except in Germany and Ireland. Portugal is top with 170.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, for every 100 boys EU-wide, a total of 124 girls
obtain a general upper secondary education qualification. Data
available show that the ratio is higher in all member states,
rising to around 141 in Finland and Denmark and as much as 185 in
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
However, "the increasing opportunities for women to remain in
education and the growing numbers of women taking upper secondary
and higher education qualifications have not completely eroded the
differences between men and women in relation to employment," says
the report.
</P>
<P>
Even among those with higher education, the unemployment rate
is seven percent for EU women compared with five percent for men.
Such differences are particularly marked in Spain, Italy and
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
