<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Vows Not to Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone said today it would not surrender to the Nigerian-led west
African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG despite intense
military pressure.
</P>
<P>
"AFRC can not surrender our sovereignty to Nigeria... and
we'll take upon fire as long as we continue to live," a junta
spokesman said, quoted by the British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC) was set up by
the junta as the country's the highest governing body immediately
after the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is in Sierra Leone mandated by west African countries
and the United Nations to restore the legitimate government
headed by president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah ousted in the coup.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting broke out last Thursday between ECOMOG and the
AFRC forces, with ECOMOG pushing near the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Planes of ECOMOG were said to flew over Freetown several hours
ago, leaving buildings near the AFRC military headquarters caught
on fire and main hospitals overwhelmed with the dead and injured.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said the junta would not make any
concession.
</P>
<P>
"We have no concession to make. We'll never negotiate the
sovereignty of our country. We'll never mortgage the loyalty of
the country to anybody," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"So it is really ironic to talk about concession," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the center of the city was now quiet
despite rumors that ECOMOG has been penetrating into it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations has called for cessation of
hostilities, citing the growing number of refugees fleeing the
country into neighboring Guinea and the rising number of civilian
casualties.
</P>
<P>
Guinea has become home to some 250,000 Sierra Leonean
refugees, most of whom fled after the first coup in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N.High Commissioner for Refugees,. some
80,000 of them fled after the coup last May, including more than
1,000 who arrived over the past week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
