<HEADLINE> UK Says Iraq Offer "not Good Enough" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair Thursday dismissed an offer by Iraq for settling the dispute
over weapon inspection as "just not good enough" and "absolutely
hopeless", but adding Britain will continue its diplomatic
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Blair was quoted by his spokesman as telling a 40-minute
cabinet meeting that the offer by Iraq to allow United Nations
(UN) weapons inspectors one visit to presidential sites was
"absolutely hopeless".
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members were told that in the past the UN had to make
several visits to Iraqi sites as one "presidential site" is
described as the size of Paris.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair said that Britain is "working flat out" to
find a diplomatic solution to the crisis and that Britain
appreciated diplomatic efforts by Russia and France, saying "we
are all working in the same direction".
</P>
<P>
But the possible timing of a military strike was not discussed
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Iraq has offered to open eight suspected
weapons sites to inspection for 60 days on condition that the UN
Secretary-General and Security Council took direct control of the
inspection.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, British Defense Secretary George Robertson
told British television that diplomacy backed with the threat of
force was starting to work with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"He's making moves now. Diplomacy is starting to work but its
only working because there is a credible threat of force as a last
resort option," said Robertson.
</P>
<P>
He added "I want diplomacy to succeed. I want him to comply. I
do not want to see military action".  
</P>
</TEXT>
