<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses US of Attempting to Heighten Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi National Assembly
Speaker Saadoun Hammadi Thursday accused the U.S. Administration
of being reluctant to find a diplomatic solution to the current
crisis over arms inspection and attempting to heighten it.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to Iraqi news agency INA, Hammadi said the
United States intends to place Iraq under its hegemony and to
prove to the world that its will alone would prevail.
</P>
<P>
"Should the United States seek the truth, it would have
welcomed Iraq's initiative, which puts forward a solution to the
crisis and addresses the core issue in question, namely,
inspection of presidential sites where Iraq is allegedly suspected
to have hidden proscribed weapons," the speaker said.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf announced in
Cairo, Egypt, on Wednesday that Iraq has agreed to open eight
presidential sites to international arms inspectors appointed by
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi stressed that the American administration has been
fomenting troubles whenever Iraq is one step closer to the
lifting of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
The world public opinion has realized that the United States'
rejection of the Iraqi initiative means ill-intention on the part
of the United States which pushes for confrontation and war rather
than peaceful solution, said Hammadi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hammadi dismissed as untrue the U.S. administration
allegations of banned weapons being concealed at presidential
sites, adding that such charges were intended to serve as a
pretext to justify a military strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"When Iraq says that there is no prohibited weapons activity
in Iraq, then it is the truth," he said. 
</P>
