<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran has called on the United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to visit Baghdad in order to
find a political solution to the current Iraq-U.N. standoff.
</P>
<P>
Local evening daily Etelaat reported Thursday that Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi made a telephone call to Annan
Wednesday night, stressing that the Iraqi crisis should be
resolved only through political ways.
</P>
<P>
"Your visit to Baghdad will have important effects" on the
resolution of the current standoff between Iraq and the United
Nations, Kharrazi told the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also exchanged views on the latest developments
in the Persian Gulf, stressing that Iraq must implement the
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi Wednesday also discussed the Iraqi crisis with his
Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa, underlining the need for a
continued diplomatic effort to avert a U.S. military strike on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Through a telephone conversation, the two foreign ministers
stressed that Iraq should observe and implement the U.N. Security
Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
With the escalation of tension between Iraq and the U.S., Iran
expressed serious concern over a possible U.S. military strike on
Baghdad, particularly on its possible impact.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami Wednesday strongly urged
international community and regional countries to prevent the
U.S. from launching the military attack. 
</P>
