<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Turkish Proposal to Settle Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Greece rejected on Thursday a
Turkish proposal to hold a high-level meeting by the end of March
this year in order to resolve the disputes between the two
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that his country could not accept the
proposal by Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem because it
included issues which were already being dealt with and reiterated
the standing Turkish stance for dialogue on all issues.
</P>
<P>
Cem reportedly presented a verbal note to the Greek ambassador
in Ankara to made the five-point proposal, which includes a
high-level meeting to define problem areas in the Aegean Sea,
formalize principles of good-neighborly relations and promote
confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
As for the Turkish proposal that committees of experts of the
two countries should meet on a bilateral basis to continue the
procedure, Reppas said that this was a European Union (EU)
Initiative and could only continue as such.
</P>
<P>
Under the EU initiative, Greece and Turkey set up committees of
experts last May to review the procedural matters of eventually
resolving their differences including the airspace limits,
territorial waters in the Aegean as well as the thorny Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Reppas stressed that Athens still respected the Madrid
Communique signed last July by Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
and Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis, which he described as a
political declaration than a treaty setting out basic principles
governing Greek-Turkish ties.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the statements by Turkey's former naval chief
that former Turkish Prime Minister Tansu Ciller and Foreign
Minister Deniz Baykal were in favor of a military confrontation
with Greece during the 1996 Imia crisis, the spokesman said that
this confirmed that Ankara did not always follow the "peaceful
path." 
</P>
</TEXT>
