<HEADLINE> Healthy Debate with Government Is Good for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 12 (Xinhua) - The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) has established a healthy working relationship with
the Government in which disagreement is expressed as openly as
consensus, the President of the CBI Colin Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at CBI London's Annual Lunch Colin said: "The CBI is
encouraged by the development of a real working partnership
between the Government and our business community."
</P>
<P>
"Naturally we do not see eye to eye all the time on every issue
but we have come to a mutual understanding that those who govern
and those who create wealth should work together as constructively
as possible," he added.
</P>
<P>
Colin said, however, there was an ongoing debate with the
Government focusing primarily on four key areas: the Budget,
Welfare to Work, Minimum Wage and union recognition.
</P>
<P>
Turning to EMU, Colin said that the CBI's view that the UK
should adopt the single currency when the time is right in terms
of convergence criteria was shared by the Government and a wide
body of opinion.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We might not be in EMU come January 1st next year but
the single currency will be in play and our trading and finance
systems need to be able to deal with it."  
</P>
