<HEADLINE> Palestinians Continue Anti-US Demonstrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Palestinians continued their
anti-U.S. and pro-Iraq demonstrations on Thursday in the West
Bank cities in defiance of orders banning such protests issued by
the Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
In Nablus and Hebron, a large number of Palestinians took to
the streets to protest against the U.S.-led military buildup in
the Gulf and the possible U.S.-led military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators also voiced their strong support to the
Iraqi government and people in their struggle against the United
States and burned U.S. and Israeli flags to express their anger
towards the Americans.
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, the demonstration was organized by the students of
Al-Hussein Ben Ali high school. When the pro-Iraq march reached
the center of the city, the protesters clashed with the Israeli
soldiers who are there guarding the Israeli Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
The protesters threw stones and molotov cocktails at the
soldiers who returned fire with rubber bullets and tear gas. No
casualties were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
In both Nablus and Hebron, the Palestinian security forces and
police tried to prevent the demonstrations from taking place, but
failed.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the Iraqi crisis and U.S. military
buildup in the Gulf, the Palestinians held a series of
demonstrations in different parts of the Palestinian territories
against the U.S. policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Such protests resulted in clashes with the Israeli soldiers and
security forces. In addition, the protesters burned Israeli and
U.S. flags and called on Iraq to fire Scud missiles at Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Both the United States and Israel believe such demonstrations
could affect the U.S. policy and worsen the situation, urging the
Palestinian leaders to stop them.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai Tuesday also sharply
criticized such demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out the dangerous consequences these protests could
produce to the security if they were out of control, Mordechai
said it is a serious mistake on the part of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) and the Palestinians to adopt such a
supportive stance towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, orders were issued by Palestinian police
commander General Ghazi Jabil on Tuesday banning pro-Iraq
activities.
</P>
<P>
But Thursday's demonstrations in Nablus and Hebron indicated
that such orders can not ban the Palestinian people from
expressing their feelings, which were badly hurt by stalled
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Feelings of anger and frustrations are on a rise among the
Palestinians nowadays due to the impasse of the peace talks with
Israel which have been stalled since last March when Israel began
construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
