<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Study Finds Landmine Crisis Can be Overcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The undeclared war to
rid the world of landmines can be won, according to a new study
of United Nations mine action programs in Afghanistan, Angola,
Cambodia and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The study released here today finds the challenge of global
demining can be met within years, not decades as previously
thought.
</P>
<P>
The study says in the most severe situations, adequate
resources can make a difference. "The experience of Afghanistan
shows this clearly: it is anticipated all high-priority minefields
in that country will be cleared within the next two years," said
the Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, which
initiated the study.
</P>
<P>
The Study also reveals that much had been learned since the
United Nations began its first humanitarian mine action program
in Afghanistan where the United Nations has proven that it can
establish truly indigenous programs.
</P>
<P>
The study points out there are some 3, 000 full-time deminers
employed by the United Nations-sponsored Afghan non-governmental
organizations. "With well-coordinated external assistance, such
program can become progressively more sustainable," say the
study.
</P>
<P>
It stresses the need to place the safety and well-being
of people at the center of any mine action program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
