<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Says IRA Ceasefire Intact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
said on Thursday the ceasefire declared by its Irish Republican
Army (IRA) last July was still held in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"It is my view that the IRA cessation is intact," local reports
quoted Adams as saying at a press conference in Belfast, the
capital of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
He also said the peace process would fail if Sinn Fein, the
political wing of IRA, was ordered to leave the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
"There are no grounds for the expulsion of our party," he said.
"Sinn Fein does not represent, we are not accountable for, and we
do not speak for any armed group."
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist Party, the chief party representing the
province's 60 percent Protestant majority, urged the British and
Irish governments to ban Sinn Fein from talks after recent
loyalist killings.
</P>
<P>
Under the talks rules, any political party linked to guerrillas
who do not eschew violence can be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
Adams denied that Sinn Fein was involved in the recent killings
and said it must not be thrown out of talks that Britain and
Ireland say offer the best prospects for generations of easing
strife between pro-British Protestants and pro-Irish Catholics.
</P>
</TEXT>
