<HEADLINE> Cyprus' New President to Be Announced Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The runoff results for new
president of Cyprus are expected to be announced Sunday night,
Chief Returning Officer Thanos Michael said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the runoff will commence at
7:00 a.m. local time (0500 GMT) and end at 17:00 p.m. local time
(1500 GMT), with 60-minute break at midday.
</P>
<P>
The runoff will take place following last Sunday's first round
of elections during which seven candidates contested for the
eighth president of the Cyprus Republic since its independence in
1960.
</P>
<P>
Two front-runners, George Iacovou, former foreign minister, and
incumbent President Glafcos Clerides, had a marginal difference.
</P>
<P>
Iacovou, backed by left wing Progress Party of the Working
People (AKEL) and the center-right Democratic Party, got 40.61
percent of the vote, while Clerides, supported by the ruling
Democratic Rally, won 40.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that last Sunday's elections ran smoothly,
Michael expressed the hope that there would be no problems in the
second round either.
</P>
<P>
Michael said posters informing voters of the correct way to
vote will be put up at the polling stations to keep the number of
invalid votes to the minimum.
</P>
<P>
The final results are expected to come out at around 23:00
p.m. local time (2100 GMT) and that the new president will be
proclaimed at the indoor stadium "Eleftheria" (Freedom) in
Nicosia around midnight, according to Michael.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief of Police Panikos Hadjiloizou also announced
Thursday that 3,380 members of the police force will be on duty
on Sunday throughout the government-controlled southern part of
the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
