<HEADLINE> UK Jobless Total Falls to Lowest Level Since 1980 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 12 (Xinhua) - The number of people out of work
in Britain fell by 12300 in January to 1.399 million, the lowest
level for 18 years, according to the latest figures released by
the Office for National Statistics (ONS).
</P>
<P>
However, the percentage of the workforce claiming benefits
because of unemployment was unchanged at 5%, with a decline of
416000 in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The claimant count is at its lowest since July 1980, and there
are 1.58 million fewer people claiming benefits than in December
1992, the last peak in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said the proximity to the holiday period may have
affected January's claimant count, because of administrative
backlogs over Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The news coincided with the Government's launch of an 8 million
pounds (10.8 million US dollars) advertising campaign to promote
its Welfare to Work program for young people.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, which will run for more than three weeks, comes
as the jobless figures show there are only 118000 young people
eligible for the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Government set a target last year of finding work for
250000 young people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
