<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Try Coup Plotters Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The trial of coup plotters the
Nigerian government brought into light last December will begin
this Saturday, the military announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six persons, including civilians and women, will face a
special military tribunal in Jos, capital of central Nigeria's
Plateau state.
</P>
<P>
Atop the list of the 26 suspects are the country's former
number two figure, Chief of General Staff Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya,
former Communications Minister Maj.-Gen. Tajudeen Olanrewaju and
former Works and Housing Minister Maj.-Gen. Abdulkarim Adisa.
</P>
<P>
The coup plotters were screened out by a special investigation
board in nearly one month's probe. At least 60 people were
invited by the panel during the investigation.
</P>
<P>
"The trial will last about one month," Rear Admiral Festus
Porbeni, Chief of Administration of the Defense Headquarters,
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He also promised that all those to face trial would be allowed
access to military lawyers.
</P>
<P>
The seven-member tribunal, set up in accordance with a law
promulgated in 1990, is led by Maj.-Gen. Sammuel Victor Malu, the
former commander of the west African peace keeping force known as
ECOMOG operating in Liberia and lately Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The military government announced on December 21 last year the
uncovery of the coup plot and 12 people, including Diya,
Olanrewaju and Adisa, have since been held.
</P>
<P>
Ehe Foreign Ministry has also indicated foreign involvement in
the plot to violently overthrow the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
