<HEADLINE> US Not to Use Nuclear Weapons in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States has not plan
to use nuclear weapons against Iraq, whatever U.S. media report,
visiting U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen announced in
Moscow on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting with Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
Cohen who arrived here Wednesday said that no U.N. authorization
is needed to use force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, he argued if Baghdad uses chemical weapons against
U.S. troops, the response will be fast and resolute.
</P>
<P>
Cohen noted that Both Russia and the U.S. want Iraq to comply
with all U.N. resolutions, though they disagree over approaches to
the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said, for his part, that using nuclear or other
weapons of mass destruction in Iraq is unthinkable and would have
a negative impact on military relations between Moscow and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
He expressed doubt that the extremely tough U.S. position
contributes to stability and security in the world.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev meanwhile flatly denied the allegation of Washington
Post that Russia in 1995 had supplied Iraq with dual purpose
equipment which could be used in the manufacture of biological
weapons. The Scud missile that Iraq has could not be used to
deliver weapons of mass destruction because they do not carry
multiple warheads, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the more than two-and-a-half-hours meeting Sergeyev and
Cohen also focused on nuclear disarmament, anti-missile defense,
European security, the situation in Bosnia and Herzegovina and the
operation of the Russia-NATO council.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Russian Defense Council secretary Andrei
Kokoshin and the visiting American defense secretary held talks on
the development of bilateral relations in defense and security
areas, according to another report. 
</P>
