<HEADLINE> Majority of Germans Still against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- With less than a year to go
before the planned formal launch of the single European currency,
the Euro, a majority of Germans still do not want to give up their
mighty German mark for the untested common currency, German press
reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The German news agency DPA today quoted a public opinion survey
conducted by the Psephos Institute as showing that 58 percent of
German voters are still against the Euro compared with only 30
percent who are in favor.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that 27 percent of Germans wants a delay
in the planned Euro launch on January 1, 1999. Only 24 percent
believe that the Euro would become a hard and stable currency like
the German mark. 
