<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Disagrees with EU on Fish Fillets Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WHO) has said that it is improper for the European
Union to impose an embargo on the imports of fish fillets from
African countries in the Lake Victoria region.
</P>
<P>
A WHO statement circulated to reporters in Dar es Salaam
Thursday indicated that the EU may have overstrained its nerves
by imposing the ban.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the spread of cholera, the EU countries last
December imposed an embargo of imports of fresh fish fillets from
Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda and other countries close to Lake
Victoria, the world's second largest fresh-water lake.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, the ban means that the country will be unable to
export 6,000 tons of fresh fish fillets to European nations,
incurring a loss of nearly seven million U.S. Dollars a year,
Zakia Meghji, Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism, said
early this month.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has appealed to the EU to lift the ban, but is
still waiting for a reply.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Geneva-based WHO has expressed a
different stand with the EU and voiced support for the African
countries.
</P>
<P>
WHO said its director-general wishes to draw attention to the
fact, although there is theoretical risk of cholera transmission
associated with some food commodities moving in international
trade, this has rarely proved significant, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The food that causes the greatest concern to importing
countries are seafood, fresh-water fish and vegetables that may
be consumed raw. Cases of cholera have occurred occasionally as
a result of eating food, usually seafood, transported across
international borders by individuals, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, the director-general wishes to recall that
the WHO has not documented any outbreak of cholera resulting from
commercially imported food, despite the fact that more than 50
countries in the world have been affected by the epidemic or
endemic cholera each year since 1961.
</P>
<P>
"Consequently the placing of embargoes on the importation of
food such as seafood, fresh-water fish and vegetables, is not an
appropriate course of action to prevent the international spread
of cholera, and can represent an additional burden on the economy
of affected countries," it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The WHO says it believes that the best way to deal with food
imports from cholera-affected areas is for importing countries to
agree, with food exporters, on good hygienic practices which need
to be followed during food handling and processing to prevent,
eliminate or minimize the risk of potential contamination, and to
set up arrangements to obtain assurance that these measures are
adequately carried out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0043 </DOCNO>
