<HEADLINE> Canada's Inco Unveils More Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The world's largest nickel
producer Inco. Ltd. has unveiled a new series of cuts in the face
of slumping nickel prices.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto-based company said it was cutting its annual
dividend to 10 cents from 40 cents, laying off more than 700
people, closing its New York office and cutting back spending on
research and development.
</P>
<P>
It would also reduce administrative budgets and eliminate cash
bonuses to be paid under an incentive plan to its senior officers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 223 million U.S. dollars would be saved with these
and other cutbacks announced three months ago.
</P>
<P>
"We want to come out of this stronger, more competitive and
profitable," Inco spokesman Jerry Rogers was quoted as saying by
reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The world price of nickel has plunged to a record low of 2.52
dollars a pound, down from 3.50 dollars in May last year, forcing
the company to take drastic moves to reduce costs. 
</P>
