<HEADLINE> Asia Crisis to Bring B.C. Near Recession, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing Asia economic
crisis will drag the Canadian province of British Columbia (B.C.)
"precariously close to recession," said a new forecast of
provincial economies.
</P>
<P>
The B.C. economy will grow only one percent this year, compared
with the national average of 3.3 percent, Canadian Imperial Bank
of Commerce said in the forecast.
</P>
<P>
"The most immediate and severe problem for B.C. comes as a
result of the economic upheaval now taking place in Asia," said
economists of the bank.
</P>
<P>
B.C. sends nearly 35 percent of its exports to Asia, compared
with a Canadian average of eight percent. Lumber, coal, pulp and
paper --the province's major exports -- have all suffered from
weaker sales in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Asia's woes also mean Canada's westcoast province
will see fewer Asian tourists this year, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
