<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Force Enters Central Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The west African peace keeping
force known as ECOMOG has entered the center of Freetown, capital
of Sierra Leone, at about 5:15 Thursday afternoon local time after
one week's intense fighting.
</P>
<P>
Col. Godwin Ugbo, spokesman of Nigeria's defense headquarters,
confirmed the news to Xinhua when reached by telephone Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But details of the move of the Nigerian-led west African
troops are not immediately available, he said, because "when we
contacted the ECOMOG field commander in Freetown this afternoon,
he went out."
</P>
<P>
"We could not know whether ECOMOG has captured the
presidential villa or not," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the fall of Freetown is a logical
result of ECOMOG's campaign as the force had by Wednesday
occupied Fourah Bay College and the surrounding villages, which
are only about one kilometer from the center of the city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a British Broadcasting Corporation report monitored
here said the junta troops are running away, although they could
open fire on an ECOMOG plane flying over from certain place in
central Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG troops are trying to capture the State House or
have already done that, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 civilians were wounded from gunshot and 80 more
others died during the heavy fighting Thursday which was
accompanied by exchange of artillery fire, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, this looks like the end of the
military regime which seized power in a coup on May 25 last year,
ousting the legitimate government led by President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Early on Thursday afternoon, a junta spokesman told BBC that
the military government would not surrender and would keep on
fighting till the last drop of blood.
</P>
<P>
However, it is predicted that it is only a question of time
for ECOMOG troops to mop up the remains of the junta soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe in three days, the city could fall," said the BBC
report. 
</P>
