<HEADLINE> More U.S. Warplanes Depart for Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Six U.S. F-16 fighter
jets took off from their domestic base on Thursday, beginning a
new round of departure of U.S. bombers and fighters for the Gulf
to join the already mighty U.S. air and naval force there for a
preparation of attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The six F-16 fighters left Shaw Air Force Base, South
Carolina, at dawn and were to arrive in Bahrain early on Friday
Gulf time after a brief stop at Lajes in the Azores.
</P>
<P>
Six eight-engine B-52 bombers, based at Barksdale Air Force
Base, Louisiana, were scheduled to leave later in the day. their
destination is a British base on the Indian Ocean island of
Diego Garcia, where they will join eight other B-52s already
stationed there.
</P>
<P>
A swing-wing B-1 bomber will also depart later in the day and
fly from Ellsworth Air Force Base, South Dakota, to Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Six F-117A stealth fighters will leave their Holloman Air
Force Base, New Mexico, on Friday to Kuwait, where they will
join six F-117As deployed there late last year for originally
scheduled attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the warplanes along with some 23 refueling
tankers and other support planes will boost the total of U.S.
attack and support aircraft in the region to about 350.
</P>
<P>
The United States has also decided to send about 2,200
Marines and up to 3,000 soldiers to the region.
</P>
<P>
The Marines aboard ships are expected to arrive in the Gulf
the weekend. And the Army troops are expected to be flown to
Kuwait within days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
