<HEADLINE> Britain to Find All Peaceful Means in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- British Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Derek Fatchett said Thursday that his country will
exhaust all diplomatic means to bring about Iraq's compliance with
the international will.
</P>
<P>
"London is determined to probe all diplomatic avenues to defuse
the crisis in a way ensuring Iraq's full commitment to Security
Council resolutions," he said at a press conference following
90-minute talks with Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid here.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have been preparing for a
military strike against Iraq over its denial of unfettered access
of the United Nations arms inspectors to the sensitive sites
suspected of hiding lethal weapons.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said the door is still open for diplomatic efforts to
take their full course, adding there is no time ceiling for these
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, however, rejected the recent proposals fielded by
various parties to solve the U.N.-Iraq standoff, saying none of
them so far met the minimum required to ensure full respect for
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has just agreed to open eight presidential compounds to
international arms experts appointed by the U.N. secretary general
Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
On the Mideast peace process, Fatchett said the current Iraqi
crisis should by no means deflect attention from the peace drive
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, who arrived here earlier in the day, said his talks
in Cairo will focus on the current Iraq-U.N. crisis and means to
settle it peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, who carried a message to President Hosni Mubarak from
British Prime Minister Tony Blair on ways to bolster bilateral
cooperation relations, cited admirable progress in Egypt's
economic reform program as conducive to deepening Anglo-Egyptian
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett's brief visit to Egypt came within the context of a
tour of the area that has so far taken him to Oman and the United
Arab Emirates. 
</P>
