<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Officials: El Nino Could Last for Some Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The El Nino weather
phenomena is expected to be lasted through spring, U.S. government
officials predicted here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"El Nino is still going strong and will for two more months,"
U.S. Commerce Secretary William M. Daley was quoted by AP as
saying. "The severe weather in California and the Southeast
unfortunately will continue."
</P>
<P>
Ants Leetmaa, director of the department's Climate Prediction
Center, noted that the current conditions are expected to prevail
for as long as three more months. Conditions should ease by
summer, he added, but even as late as fall, some El Nino remnants
could remain.
</P>
<P>
"We think that the character of the rain response in areas like
Florida, southern California or central California is going to be
very much like it has been for the last month or two months,"
Leetmaa said. "What you'll have is episodic events, there'll be
periods where it dries out then again there'll be periods of very
heavy storms like we've seen in the past."
</P>
<P>
Some forecasters are predicting that conditions could then
switch to the opposite phase, called La Nina, "which could be
equally destructive for the United States," Leetmaa said.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, a periodic warming and air pressure change in the
eastern Pacific Ocean, causes weather changes worldwide. This time
it has been particularly serious for California, where storms have
undermined roads and buildings and driven people from their homes.
</P>
<P>
Daley said damage estimates so far range from 250 million
dollars to 1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino of 1982-83 caused an estimated 2.5 billion dollars
in damage in the United States, Daley said, noting that property
values have risen sharply since then.
</P>
<P>
Leetmaa's forecast for February through April calls for wetter
than normal conditions to continue in California, Arizona, New
Mexico, Texas and Florida. Meanwhile, the Puget Sound region,
Montana and the Great Lakes, Middle Atlantic and Ohio Valley seem
likely to be drier than usual.
</P>
<P>
The temperature forecast calls for warmer than normal for the
Pacific Coast and northern tier of states east to the Great Lakes
and colder than usual in Texas, the Gulf Coast and Atlantic Coast
states north to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
However, experts stressed that in El Nino years there tend to
be fewer than normal hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean and it can
produce milder than normal winters in much of the country. This
winter, for example, has been the third warmest on record,
potentially saving as much as 10 percent on heating bills for many
Americans, Leetmaa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Parliament Passes 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- After seven days' heated
debate, Angola's National Assembly Thursday passed the national
budget for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was passed with 112 votes for, 12 votes
against and 73 abstentions, is the first balanced one made by the
government in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Defense and domestic expenditures take up the highest
percentages in the budget, accounting for 5.76 percent and 4.56
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, parliament adopted the 1998-2000 economic
rehabilitation program, which is aimed to restore the country's
economy after the civil war and improve people's living standard.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Franca van-Dunem expressed satisfaction over
the adoption of the budget and the rehabilitation program
Thursday, saying that the budget is practical, although the
capital prescribed in it is far from enough.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government will govern Angola this year
under the circumstances of real peace in the country, which is
the first time for 22 years since its independence. 
</P>
