<HEADLINE> Prodi Reaffirms Italy's Bid to Become Founding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Romano Prodi of
Italy Thursday reaffirmed his country's demand to become a
founding member of the single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
"Italy has made all efforts to meet the fiscal criteria
required for joining the the European Monetary Union," said Prodi
in a speech at the opening ceremony of the new fairground of the
southern Germany city of Munich.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the sustainability of the fiscal discipline imposed
by his government, which has been doubted occasionally by some
other European Union countries, including Germany, Prodi said that
"a culture of fiscal stability" had been introduced in Italy,
which would have an irreversible effect on the state budget.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is due to launch the Euro on January 1,
1999. Final decisions on which countries would be allowed to join
the club will be made early May. 
</P>
