<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The first priority of the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
in the area of employment in the coming year is to step up efforts
to help the unemployed re-enter the labor market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Friday, Secretary for
Education and Manpower Joseph W.P. Wong briefed on the
government's major initiative on employment and labor in 1998-99
which include measures to improve labor relations, safety and
health at work.
</P>
<P>
The Education and Manpower Bureau called a high-level meeting
last month to work out ways to tackle the problem of unemployment
increase in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
Those who attended the meeting studied the latest labor market
situation and discussed ways to help the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Bureau officials also had meetings with employers' groups to
explore further scope for cooperation between the government, the
training bodies and employers on tailor-made retraining programs
which will provide new and transferable skills for the unemployed
and enable them to secure and hold down a job.
</P>
<P>
And a comprehensive guide to employment and training will be
published shortly which sets out all the employment, training and
social welfare services available to the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department will further improve its unemployment
services by setting up a second employment and guidance center for
the new arrivals in September and completing the computerization
of the entire local employment services in 11 centers by April,
Wong said.
</P>
<P>
Greater efforts would be made to strengthen the health and
safety of workers at work, which include implementation of the
Occupational Safety and Health Ordinance which came into force in
May last year.  
