<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Spring Feels Like Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Temperatures in Shanghai
climbed to unseasonably warm 27 degrees Celsius today, a change
which perhaps falsely heralded the early arrival of Spring.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists noted that today was the warmest February
13 on record since 1873, with records for the past 120 years
showing that temperatures have surpassed 20 degrees Celsius on
only 13 occassions.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures over the past week climbed by over 10 Celsius
degrees, with cold drizzle replaced by warm sunshine, according to
the experts.
</P>
<P>
With bright sun shining overhead, Shanghailanders stayed
indoors or attempted to find shady areas so as to escape the
heatwave. Children donned shortsleeve shirts, and shops witnessed
brisk sales of cold drinks and sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
A relatively weak cold front from the north has enabled areas
in the lower and middle reaches of the Yangtze to enjoy a warm
air mass, according to local meterologists. They also pointed to
the sharp contrast in the sustained periods of rain characteristic
of earlier periods.
</P>
<P>
While temperatures are not expected to drop significantly in
coming days, local residents should be fully prepared for
the sudden return of a cold front from the north, said experts.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu. Zhejiang, Anhui and various other neighboring
provinces in the lower reaches of the Yangtze River Valley also
experienced higher than normal temperatures today.
</P>
<P>
Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang Prvince, recorded a
a high Friday temperature of 27 degress Celsius, the highest
spring-like temperature over the past two decades.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
