<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hispanic Births Reach Record High in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of babies being
born to Hispanic women in the United States has reached a record
high to 18 percent of the nation's total although Hispanic
residents make 10.3 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
The National Center for Health Statistics said in a report
released Thursday that 679,768 babies were born to Hispanic women
in 1995, the latest year for which complete data are available.
The figure is up from 532,249 in 1989, when 14 percent of all
babies born in the United States had Hispanic mothers.
</P>
<P>
The report indicates that much of the increase in Hispanic
births is the result of high fertility rates among
Mexican-Americans. About 70 percent of the babies born to Hispanic
women in 1995 were born to women of Mexican heritage, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times newspaper said Friday that the study's
findings strongly imply that, as a result of high levels of
immigration and a high birth rate, people of Mexican heritage are
poised to become a major economic, political and cultural force in
the coming decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
