<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strategic Plan for Tourism Development Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
formulating a strategic plan to sustain a long term vision for
the development of tourism in the country, President Robert
Mugabe said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the Zimbabwe International Travel Expo in
Harare, Mugabe said a tourism revolving fund would be established
soon to enable further investment by indigenous entrepreneurs in
the industry.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, also intended to launch a massive
rehabilitation exercise of the national parks as the pillars of
Zimbabwean tourism.
</P>
<P>
"Since transport and tourism are inextricable partners,"
Mugabe said, "the government is preparing a number of programs
directed at obviating the bottlenecks existing within the
domestic and international air transport networks."
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the tourism industry reveal that more
than 3.4 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (200 million U.S. Dollars)
was realized from the sector in 1997 compared to 2.4 billion
Zimbabwean Dollars (140 million U.S. Dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"There is, therefore, no doubt that tourism is the fastest
growing sector of Zimbabwe's economy," Mugabe said, adding that
"given the appropriate environmental conditions, the industry
could play a leading role in employment creation and foreign
exchange earnings."
</P>
<P>
On the economy, he said the government was committed to a
process of economic reform to improve the well being of the
people.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe remains committed to the sustainable growth of the
economy and the maintenance of peace and stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
This year's travel expo attracted more than 150 buyers
compared to last year's 75. It was being attended by 160
exhibitors compared with 106 last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
