<HEADLINE> China Values Danish Ties, Says Chinese Vice-Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COPENHAGEN, February 13 (Xinhua) - China attaches importance to
its ties with Denmark and treasures the friendly, cooperative
relationship established between peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said this on Friday while
talking with Mrs Marianne Jelved, Denmark's acting prime minister
and minister of economy and Nordic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Denmark was among the first western countries to establish
diplomatic relations with China, and there is no existing cardinal
dispute between the two counties, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China and Denmark have many mutual interests in
their efforts to uphold world peace and promote mutual development
of human beings, the vice-premier added.
</P>
<P>
As the bilateral relationship developed rapidly in recent years
and the cooperation fields expanded, the economies of China and
Denmark have huge potentiality for cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mrs Marianne Jelved agreed with the vice-premier's comments on
political and economic relations. She said Denmark would exert its
efforts to push forward to a new stage the economic and trade
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At the request of his host, Li also gave a briefing on China's
opinions on the financial crisis in Asia and the situation of
economic reforms in China.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Li held talks with Danish Minister of Food
Henrik Dam Kristensen. Both agreed they would make efforts to
promote beneficial cooperation in agriculture, fisheries, food
processing, infrastructure construction and education.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li arrived here Thursday on a five-day visit to
Denmark. Talks was held between him and Danish Foreign Minister
Niels Helveg Petersen soon after his arrival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
