<HEADLINE> Lesotho Police Open Fire on Strikers, Kill Woman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 13 (Xinhua) -- A woman was killed and
scores of poeple injured after Lesotho police opened fire on
striking factory workers early Friday, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Six people were admitted to hospital with serious injuries and
43 others were treated as out-patients following the shooting,
the SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Workers and management at the CGM factory at Ha-Thetsane,
southeast of the capital Maseru, have been involved in a wage
dispute since last week, and the workers held management hostage
on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The police were called in and rescued the factory managers,
but the workers refused to go home and stayed on the company's
premises overnight, the SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
The company was given an eviction order on Friday morning and
the police were called in to carry it out.
</P>
<P>
"While leaving the premises, striking workers started throwing
stones at the factory, some hitting the police. Nearby factories
were also damaged," the SAPA quoted Lesotho Police Commissioner
Bodutu Makoaba as saying.
</P>
<P>
Workers of nearby factories also joined the strike and pelted
the police with stones. During the process, the police responded
by opening fire, injuring dozens of people.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Marematlou Freedom Party leader Vincent Malebo
condemned the "wanton" shooting, stressing that it happened to
mostly silent and untempestuous women who were only waiting for a
reply to a list of demands to the CGM management.
</P>
<P>
He said it was unfortunate that the shooting happened at a
time when there was need to concentrate on preparations for
Lesotho's general elections late April or early May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
