<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Leone Junta Officers Flee to Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG ) has taken control of almost the whole Freetown,
capital of Sierra Leone, with many senior officers of the junta
having fled to neighboring Liberia, the Nigerian military said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Godwin Ugbo, spokesman of the Nigerian Defence Headquarters,
told Xinhua that the whereabouts of the junta leader, Johnny Paul
Koroma, is not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
"Koroma has run away and is likely in Monrovia now, but it is
not officially announced that he is there," said Ugbo, who is the
Acting Director of the Department of Defense Information.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a helicopter carrying most of the senior
officers of the Koroma government has landed in Monrovia, capital
of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
They have been held by the ECOMOG headquarters in Monrovia for
questioning and interrogation.
</P>
<P>
"So actually, most of the senior officers of the Sierra
Leonean army are no more there. They have either deserted or run
away. Some of them are seen in hiding."
</P>
<P>
As for the fate of Koroma and his senior officers, Ugbo said:
"You wait until we hear from the ECOWAS headquarters."
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) sent
ECOMOG to Freetown to seek for the restoration of the legitimate
government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah ousted in a coup last
May.
</P>
<P>
Under intense international pressure, the junta agreed last
October to return power to Kabbah's government by April 22 this
year but later refuse to implement the peace accord to that
effect.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting between ECOMOG and the junta forces
erupted last Thursday when the former claimed one of its soldiers
on surveillance duty had his leg ripped off by a landmine laid by
junta men.
</P>
<P>
After one week's fighting, ECOMOG forces entered the center of
Freetown, meeting with minimal resistence because the majority of
the junta have defected.
</P>
<P>
"More than 70 percent of the junta soldiers have surrendered
to ECOMOG. So we have been taking refuge of so many of them,"
said Ugbo.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeepers have taken over the State House, which is the
military headquarters of the junta, the parliament building,
presidential villa and other strategic postions.
</P>
<P>
According to him, ECOMOG is mopping up some areas of Freetown
where the remaining members of the RUF and other junta soldiers
who have not surrendered, are entrenched.
</P>
<P>
The Revolutionary United Front (RUF), which has been fighting
successive governments of the tiny west African country since
early 1990s, became allied to the junta after the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group formerly built strongholds in some parts of
Freetown and that is where ECOMOG is going to drive them away.
</P>
<P>
The defense spokesman said ECOWAS only recognizes the armed
forces of Sierra Leone and the RUF rebels should surrender.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say how long ECOMOG will need to wipe out the
RUF fighters, whose existence is said to have caused the trouble
in Sierra Leone for a long time.
</P>
<P>
As for whether President Kabbah could be reinstated earlier
than the April 22 deadline, Ugbo said it is a matter up to the
ECOWAS headquarters to decide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0089 </DOCNO>
