<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministry Calls for Strict Control of Methanol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
Chemical Industry recently issued an emergency circular
instructing local chemical manufacturers to monitor, establish
special files and conduct follow-up checks of product usage.
</P>
<P>
The document was issued following a recent incident in north
China's Shanxi Province which led to the deaths of 27 people and
the hospitalization of an additional 1,000-odd people who consumed
spirits containing excessive levels of methyl alcohol.
</P>
<P>
The circular -- "Emergency Notice on Further Strengthening
Supervision and Control over the Production and Marketing of
Methanol -- calls for increased supervision and control over
dangerous chemical substances, including methyl alcohol.
</P>
<P>
Local departments in charge of the chemical industry have been
ordered to adopt measures to strictly prevent methanol and other
dangerous alcoholic beverages from reaching the public via illegal
channels.
</P>
<P>
The circular calls for an appropriate administrative system
which will prevent the occurrence of further incidents in the
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
