<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Calls for Agricultural Policy Changes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) has called on Sub-Saharan African countries to
change their agricultural policies to halt the process of natural
resource degradation.
</P>
<P>
In a press release reaching here Friday, FAO said that a
regional meeting was scheduled to be held in Addis Ababa on
February 16-20 to seek urgent action to transform agriculture and
rationalize natural resources in Sub-Sahara.
</P>
<P>
In a report to be delivered at the regional meeting, FAO said
that many countries in the region failed to adopt environmentally
sustainable agricultural practices to improve productivity and
counter the process of natural resource degradation.
</P>
<P>
Failure to adopt agricultural technologies and practices which
are not only productivity-improving, but also environmentally
sustainable, has resulted in a dismally poor performance of the
agricultural sector in the region, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Except for rapid population growth, the report said,
policy failure to technologically transform agriculture on a
sustainable basis and to rationalize the exploitation of forest
and other natural resources should be regarded as "the main factor
of the current high rate of resource-degradation in Sub-Saharan
Africa."
</P>
<P>
It warned that Sub-Saharan Africa risks being marginalized
from the mainstream world economy because of the failture of many
countries in the region to change their agricultural policies.
</P>
<P>
It called for an urgent need for the formation of an environmental
information system to provide key information about sound management
and use of natural resources to decision-makers, scientists, engineers
and technologists in the region.
</P>
<P>
Tax and other incentives which encourage deforestation should
be eliminated and replaced by schemes to encourage planting and
reforestation, the report stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
