<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Valentine's Day Means "More" for Thais </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Valentine's Day this year is
more demanding for loving Thais, as the cost of romance is soaring
due to the country's economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Young lovers have to pay twice as much as they did a year
earlier for red roses, symbol of the "day of love" as Thais call
it.
</P>
<P>
Florists said that prices for imported roses, especially those
from the Netherlands, will double this Valentine's Day from
100-200 baht (2.2- 4.3 U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Many florists predicted a gloomy festival as high prices stop
lovers from purchasing. And the weekend holiday will also play a
part as Thais used to send flowers to their loved ones' office
instead of their home.
</P>
<P>
However, rays of hope remain for local roses dealers due to the
belt-tightening budget and the "Buy Thai" campaign.
</P>
<P>
Compared with roses imported from overseas, locally grown roses
are much cheaper, although their prices have also skyrocketed to
200 baht (4.3 dollars) from 50-100 baht (1.1-2.2 dollars) last
year.
</P>
<P>
Facing the price hike of roses, many Thais resorted to pagers
since paging sweet words to their loved ones will cost only three
baht each time.
</P>
<P>
During the Valentine's Day season, major paging companies are
expected to receive 40 to 50 percent more calls than ordinary
days. Some companies have to advise their subscribers to send
their messages in advance.
</P>
<P>
A local newspaper reported that a survey showed that each
Bangkok resident plans to spend an average of 400 baht (8.7
dollars) to celebrate the "day of love", down 30 percent from last
year's average of 600 baht (13 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The survey launched by the Thai Farmers Research Center said
that about 23.5 percent of the people questioned intend to buy
flowers, 21.9 percent want to send cards, another 21.8 percent
prefer chocolate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
