<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Kenya Sign Agreement on Quarantine for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- China and Kenya signed on
Friday an agreement under which Kenya will be responsible for
quarantine and health requirements for the ratites to be exported
from it to China.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister for Agriculture Musalia Mudavadi and Chinese
Ambassador to Kenya An Yongyu signed the agreement on behalf of
their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
After signing the agreement, the Kenyan minister said that
Kenya and China went into a "completely new area which is not
explored" in the cooperation of the two countries, adding that
"we will continue to work very closely".
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, the Chinese ambassador noted that "it is
an import step of the cooperation between our two countries in
the field of agriculture and livestock".
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Kenyan Veterinary Services shall be
responsible for the implementation of quarantine and inspection
procedures and the issuance of certificates for the export
ratites including ostriches, rheas and emus.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side shall send veterinarians to farms of export
ratites, related isolation premises, testing laboratories and
quarantine facilities and cooperate with Kenyan veterinarians in
making inspection and quarantine.
</P>
<P>
The agreement shall come into force on Friday and will be
valid for a period of 5 years from that date.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that an agreement was signed last December to
set up a joint venture of ostrich farm between China National
Aero-Technology Import and Export Corporation, and Kenya's Maasai
Ostrich Farm.
</P>
<P>
Jim Gardiner of Maasai Ostrich Farm disclosed at the signing
ceremony that China would import about 10,000 adult ostriches
from the joint venture in the next three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
