<HEADLINE> Dream Tournament Opens with Canada and Russia Big Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Men's ice hockey medal
round, so-called Dream Tournament, began with favorites Canada and
Russia scoring their big victories respectively Friday night at the
Nagano Winter Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
World champion Canada, who scored twice at the first and second
period apiece, trounced Belarus 5-0, while Russia, backed by forward
Alexei Yashin's three goals, downed Kazakstan 9-2 easily.
</P>
<P>
The Dream Tournament were joined by top six teams of the World
Championships and two winners from the preliminaries, where eight
teams had been divided into two groups to contend for the seats of the
medal round.
</P>
<P>
Kazakstan and Belarus sailed into the medal round as group winners
in the preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
The opening day's game also featured game between defending
champion Sweden and the United States. The Swede got off to a
storming start to a 4-2 victory over highly-fancied team the Americans
ealier Friday.
</P>
<P>
The match witnessed three goals within several seconds during the
first period. Chris Chelios put the Americans one up after 11 minutes
and 10 seconds, but NHL 1996 Rookie of the Year Daniel Alfredson
levelled the scores on a powerplay at 12:26.
</P>
<P>
Modano put one past Swedish goalie Tommy Salo to give the United
States the lead at 12:50, and the Americans went off the ice at the
end of the first 2-1 up and having outshot the Swedes 12-5.
</P>
<P>
It was downhill for the United States from that time. Patric
Kjellberg beat American goalie Mike Richter to tie the game at 21:50,
while Alfredson scored again to give Sweden the lead at 31:33. Both
Alfredson goals were assisted by Peter Frosberg, NHL Rookie of the
Year for 1995.
</P>
<P>
Mats Sundin scored the fourth goal for Sweden with three minutes to
go in the third period.
</P>
<P>
After the match, Sundin said:"I think we came out in the first
period and we didn't play as good as we wanted to. We were changing
chances back and forth with them and if you do that,it is going to be
very dangerous.
</P>
<P>
"So we came out in the second period and controlled the game a
little bit more. And we played the way we wanted to play," he said.
</P>
<P>
In another match Friday afternoon, Czech Republic defeated Finland
3-0.
</P>
<P>
After a scoreless first period, Czech's Patera scored at nine
minutes and nine seconds of the second period. Martin Rucinsky passed
the puck to Patera beside the net, who attempted to pass it a waiting
teammate out front but the puck hit a Finland defender's skate and was
deflected into the net.
</P>
<P>
Czech kept the pressure on and scored less than five minutes into
the thrid period. Robert Reichel dallied with the puck behind the
Finland net, psyched out goalie Jarmo Myllys and slipped it in the
side. The assist went to Robert Lang.
</P>
<P>
With both team one man short, Jaromir Jagr grabbed the puck in his
end, raced down the ice and passed it to Vladimir ruzicka who tapped
it in at 8:40 to make the final scoring.
</P>
<P>
After Friday's competitions, Canada and Sweden led Group D with one
win while Russia and Czech Republic headed Group C.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Belarus are playing in Group D. Group C
features Kazakstan and Finland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
