<HEADLINE> 20,000 Hungarian Victims to Get Swiss Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- About 20,000 Hungarian
Holocaust survivors are expected to receive a support of 400
U.S. dollars each from a Swiss Fund, a press release in Bern
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Rolf Bloch, President of the Swiss Fund for Needy Victims of
the Holocaust, handed over the support money Thursday to a group
of survivor representatives in a ceremony in Budapest, Hungary.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 Hungarian victims have already received such a
grant, says a press release.
</P>
<P>
The payments in Hungary are based on a distribution plan by the
World Jewish Restitution Organization (WJRO) for Eastern Europe
and the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
This plan foresees the creation of national systems in all the
countries involved, in co-operation with Jewish communities and
local survivors organizations.
</P>
<P>
The systems are designed to collect applications from all
Jewish Holocaust survivors and to distribute the contents of the
special fund in an efficient and just manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
