<HEADLINE> Deceased First Vice President of Sudan Buried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The First Vice President of
Sudan el-Zubeir Mohammed Salih and other victims of a Thursday
plane crash were buried here Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the victims were transported to Khartoum Thursday
evening from the crash site at Nasir town in southern Sudan, some
800 kilometers from the capital Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
The funeral was attended by Sudanese President Omar Hassan
Ahmed al-Bashir, the National Assembly Speaker Hassan Abdulla al
Turabi, cabinet ministers, diplomats and thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
The plane had 57 people on board when it crashed, reportedly
because of a storm. So far eight bodies have been found, 31
survived and 18 are still missing.
</P>
<P>
Among those survivors is Minister of Culture and Information
and government spokesman Tabib Ibrahim Mohammed Khair. He has
categorically denied that the plane was shot down by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
"It was due to the storm that pushed the plane off the runway
into the Sobat river at the end of the air strip," he said.
</P>
<P>
The John Garang movement, a major rebel faction in southern
Sudan, has issued a statement Thursday claiming it had shot down
the plane over the city of Wau in Bahr Al Ghazal state.
</P>
<P>
However, the plane had in fact crashed in the Nasir town
overlooking the Sobat river, some 500 kilometers from Wau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
