<HEADLINE> HK's Anson Chan on New Appointments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Administrative Secretary of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Anson Chan
voiced full confidence in the three newly appointed principal
officials Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Her comment came shortly after the Central People's Government
appointed the three officials to new positions upon the nomination
and recommendation of SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
Kwong Ki-chi, current secretary for the treasury, has been
appointed Secretary for Information Technology and Broadcasting.
Denise Yue, secretary for trade and industry, has been appointed
Secretary for the Treasury. Chau Tak-hay, current Secretary for
Broadcasting, Culture and Sport, has been appointed Secretary for
Trade and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The appointments will take effect in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Anson Chan, who heads the 180,000-strong civil service, pointed
 out that the three officials "are experienced public
administrators with extensive knowledge of the portfolios they are
about to take up".
</P>
<P>
"Both the Chief Executive and I are confident that they are
best suited for their new appointments," she added.
</P>
<P>
The SAR administration announced Wednesday the reorganized
institutional framework for information technology-related
matters.
</P>
<P>
Under the rationalization exercise, the Broadcasting, Culture
and Sport Bureau (BCSB) will be restructured as the Information
Technology and Broadcasting Bureau (ITBB).
</P>
<P>
While retaining the policy on broadcasting matters, the
reorganized bureau will undertake policy responsibility for
overall information technology development in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
BCSB's current responsibility for arts, culture, sports and
recreation will be transferred to the Home Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The plan to put all matters relating to information technology
and the related areas of broadcasting and telecommunications under
the charge of a single bureau was announced by the chief executive
in his policy address last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
