<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD: Disclosures Might Have Eased Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior United Nations
official said here on Wednesday that better financial disclosure
by commercial banks might have given some early warning signals on
the financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Rubens Ricupero, Secretary-general of the UN Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD), was speaking at a meeting of the
UNCTAD Intergovernmental Working Group of Experts on International
Standards of Accounting and Reporting (ISAR).
</P>
<P>
He said the Asian crisis "is essentially a banking crisis, at
least in some aspects, which started with an ill-performing
banking system, was compounded by excessive overseas borrowing, an
unsustainable property and equity boom and ended with massive
short-term outflow, a free fall in the currency and general loss
of confidence.
</P>
<P>
"The worst might have been avoided, or at least contained, if
there had been some early warning signals."
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to experts in accounting and reporting from
more than 50 countries and about 20 professional associations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
