<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares End Weekly Trading 2 Percent Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This was the fourth straight losing session in the week.
Combining the five trading sessions together, the market lost
211.26 points or 2.01 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
Concerns over the region's financial situation, in particular
Indonesia's currency crisis, and fears of interest rate hikes
dampened the market.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip indicator Hang Seng Index dropped 109.42 points,
or 1.03 percent, to open at 10,510.61 Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
It lost 363.33 points, or 3.42 percent, to close at 10,256.70
at midday.
</P>
<P>
Property stocks were particularly weak, plunging 6.20 percent,
followed by commerce and industry, shedding 4.32 percent, and
finance, down 3.63 percent.
</P>
<P>
The value of turnover was 9,351 million HK dollars (1,199
million U.S. dollars), higher than Thursday's 8,320 million HK
dollars (1,067 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The market had a good start for the week Monday with the index
gaining 387.29 points, or 3.69 percent, to close at 10,873.15, the
 highest so far this year.
</P>
<P>
But the strong gains were soon erased by profit-taking, with
the index losing 13.48 points Tuesday and another 66.26 points
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The market continued downward with the loss of another 173.38
points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local brokers predicted some further pressure next week but saw
some support around 10,000 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
