<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia's Super Corridor Project Continues  Despite Economic Woes (1)  by Wu Dingbao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Despite the financial and
economic problems facing the country, the Malaysian government has
pledged to carry on its Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) project as
scheduled, which according to officials is progressing well.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia had to put off several giant development projects
worth billions of U.S. dollars following the financial crisis
prevailing in the region since last July.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Thursday that the
financial and economic problems have not affected the MSC, a 750
square kilometer area stretching from the Kuala Lumpur city center
southward to the new Kuala Lumpur international airport in Sepang,
designated as a hub for the development of multimedia products and
services.
</P>
<P>
"If there is any effect at all, it is to accelerate the
project," Mahathir told reporters at a news conference Thursday
after the first day of the two-day second meeting of the
International Advisory Panel (IAP) on the MSC.
</P>
<P>
The first IAP meeting was held in California on January 16 last
year, and the current second meeting drew 25 information
technology experts and telecommunications chiefs who discussed
various subjects relating to the implementation and policies of
the MSC.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia described the discussions as "very useful" because the
meeting enabled the Multimedia Development Corporation (MDC),
which oversees the overall development of the MSC project, and the
government to learn the ideas, shortcomings and recommendations
from the participants needed to make the MSC a success.
</P>
<P>
"The MSC project will go on as scheduled. There is no need to
put it on hold," Mahathir pledged.
</P>
<P>
Some critics have labeled the MSC as an "ambitious, grandiose
mega project." Mahathir said, "I will admit that it is an
ambitious project but it is not for us Malaysians to implement
alone. We will participate actively of course, but the MSC is for
the whole world."
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government invests mainly in the infrastructure
for the high-technology hub. Land would be parceled out and sold
to investors wishing to set up their facilities.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of the local currency ringgit had eroded some
of the government's capacity, Mahathir said, "But we can still
carry on. So the MSC will go on."
</P>
<P>
Barely a year since Malaysia first launched the MSC, the MSC
project is progressing well ahead of schedule and the response to
it has been beyond the government's expectations.
</P>
<P>
A total of 103 companies have so far been granted the MSC
status, with 80 already operating and the rest 23 setting up their
operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia's Super Corridor Project Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since April last year, 178 applications have been received for
MSC status with 39 percent from foreign companies, 35 percent from
Malaysian companies and 26 percent from joint ventures between
Malaysian and foreign companies, according to statistics by the
MDC.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is beginning to see the value created from the
Information Age business.
</P>
<P>
The companies which have applied for MSC status are projected
to have a combined revenue of around 13 billion ringgit (3.4
billion U.S. dollars) by the fifth year of operation, according to
the MDC.
</P>
<P>
The projected profit for the same period would be close to 5
billion ringgit (1.3 billion dollars) on the back of an investment
of around 4 billion ringgit (1.05 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The MDC statistics on the MSC status companies showed increased
investment in high value-added activities with revenue to
investment ratio of approximately 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
Several of the world's top information technology experts and
company chiefs have expressed strong confidence in the MSC, saying
the project will be a great success.
</P>
<P>
They expressed their commitment to the project during the IAP
meeting and even pledged for new and further investments in MSC.
</P>
<P>
Motorola Chairman Gary L. Tooker and Siemens Executive Vice
President Axel Haas said that their companies were committed to
expanding business in MSC.
</P>
<P>
Silicon Graphics Chairman Bob Bishop said, "Despite the money
crisis, the MSC will be a catalyst to pull Malaysia and the entire
region forward. There is major progress from the last meeting.
Facilities are more visible. Planning are more concrete."
</P>
<P>
BCE Chief Executive Officer Lynton Wilson said: "While current
unrest in Asian markets may delay development in the short term,
the fundamental concept (of the MSC) is sound and is firmly backed
by the highest levels of the government."
</P>
<P>
They believed that the MSC's target to operate at full capacity
by 2005 is achievable despite Asia's current economic turmoil as
the project's fundamental concept is sound.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia assures the companies in the MSC that the restrictions
imposed by the government on certain kinds of information would
not apply as far as the MSC is concerned.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia pledged to implement intellectual property rights in
the MSC's Cyberlaws, which was seen as an important factor that
could ensure the success of the MSC project.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise we cannot attract a lot of these companies....it is
also in the interest of our own people because unless we protect
the intellectual property, a lot of people in the country will
lose their money," Mahathir said, adding that in addition, it
would help ensure that the interest of foreign companies in the
country is duly protected.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is also considering providing safety net for companies
on the edge of bankruptcy. "If any MSC companies fail, we will
provide some form of safety net for them," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia also pledged to supply sufficient knowledge workers to
meet the need of the MSC.
</P>
<P>
Some 23,000 knowledge workers would be needed over the next
five years by companies operating in the MSC, with 59 percent of
them in the information technology field, according to a survey by
the MDC.
</P>
<P>
The MDC is offering attractive financial and non-financial
incentives to educational institutions and companies providing
training services.
</P>
<P>
Foreign knowledge workers would also be allowed to work in the
MSC status companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
