<HEADLINE> IOC to Review Use of Marijuana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee said Friday that it will set up a working group to review
its policy relating to the use of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
An announcement released by the IOC Friday said its president Juan
Antonio Samaranch decided the same day to appoint a working group
comprising four vice presidents to do the job.
</P>
<P>
"This working group will have to submit recommendations to the IOC
as to future policy and the procedure to be followed so that the IOC
may review its rules as soon as possible, taking into account all
elements of concern," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The officials named to the working group Pal Schmitt, Richard W.
Pound, Anita Defrantz and vice president-elect Judge Keba Mbaye and
Prince Alexandre de Merode, chairman of the IOC Medical Commission.
</P>
<P>
IOC Director General Francois Carrard will serve as its secretary.
</P>
<P>
The IOC made the decision after the Court of Arbitration for Sports
reinstated Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati's gold medal in the
men's giant slalom event on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The IOC announced on Wednesday that Rebagliati was disqualified and
striped of the gold after a dope test found traces of marijuana.
</P>
</TEXT>
