<HEADLINE> German Economic Growth Slowed Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economy failed to
sustain an impressive upturn in the summer of 1997 and started to
slow down towards the end of the year, the German Economics
Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
After a clear expansion during the summer, there was only a
slight increase in gross domestic product (GDP) in the fourth
quarter, said the ministry in its lastest economic report.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the overall deceleration mainly to slower
output growth in the manufacturing industry, with domestic orders
remaining flat and foreign demand down three percent compared with
the fourth quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite a post-war record unemployment of 4.8 million in
January 1998, the ministry said it had seen some "first positive
signals" on the job market, with stabilization of the job
situation apparently underway in western Germany.
</P>
<P>
In the eastern half of the country, however, an end to job
losses was not in sight yet, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
