<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Says Washington Post Allegation Groundless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Friday dismissed as
groundless a Washington Post newspaper allegation that U.N. arms
inspectors have found documents indicating Russia had provided
Iraq with equipment for producing biological materials.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said that by leaking such false news to
the Washington Post, the U.S. administration is intending to harm
the persistent efforts Russia has been exerting to find a
diplomatic way out of Iraq-U.N. standoff.
</P>
<P>
"Leaking such false information is an exercise of media and
diplomatic terrorism against Russia," said the spokesman, quoted by
the Iraq News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. ploy was aimed at "playing down Russia's
neutral responsible position vis-a-vis Iraq's legitimate demands
for lifting the embargo and restructuring the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM)" charged with eliminating Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the timing of such false accusation also "aims to
cover up espionage and political service offered to U.S.
administration by U.S. officials and inspectors on UNSCOM and its
teams functioning in Iraq".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraqi Presidential Office Adviser Lt. General Amir
as-Saadi categorically denied the U.S. paper allegation of a 1995
deal between Iraq and Russia for the purchase of 5,000-liter
fermentation tanks, a so-called dual-purpose device that can be
used to produce biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
As-Saadi said that in 1995, Iraqi industrial authority was
planning to build an animal feed plant, and ordered Russian
fermentation tanks with a capacity of 3,000 cubic meters, or 3
million liters, appropriate for the production of fodder, rather
than prohibited germs.
</P>
<P>
"All the said measures were taken with the acknowledgement of
UNSCOM and under its supervision", stressed as-Saadi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
