<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Dragged Down by Asian Market Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian stocks closed
lower Friday, dragged down by falls on Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 21.3 points, or 0.8 percent, to
2653.0, despite Wall Street's Dow Jones Industrial Average rising
55.05 points to 8369.60.
</P>
<P>
"The market's gone down, I think it's following Asia," said a
broker from Hartley Poynton.
</P>
<P>
Following weaker sessions Thursday, both the Tokyo and Hong
Kong markets traded down during their morning sessions.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei 225 index closed down 383.92 points at 16791.01, a
fall of 2.2 percent on the day, while the Hang Seng index closed
down 363.33 points at 10256.70.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 17.5 points, or 1.49 percent, to
1156.0 while the all industrials ended down 27.6 points, or 0.61
percent, to 4532.4.
</P>
<P>
The weakening of industrial stocks, including the interest-rate
sensitive bank sector, came despite bullish news about inflation.
</P>
<P>
Official wages statistics released Friday showed average weekly
ordinary time earnings rose at an annual rate of 3.7 percent,
lower than the median forecast of 4.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank lost 13.8 cents, Westpac lost seven,
ANZ shed one and Commonwealth Bank dropped two cents.
</P>
<P>
In the resource sector, major miner BHP lost 42 cents while Rio
Tinto gained 20. Oil and gas takeover target Petroz lost five
cents while Cultus Petroleum closed flat at 2.65 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 20.9 points, or 1.80 percent, to 1142.4
while gold bullion fell 1.90 to 299.05 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 345.03 million shares valued at 845.05
million Australian dollars (566.18 million U.S. dollars) with
falls outnumbering rises 653 to 470.  
</P>
</TEXT>
