<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weaker on Asia Downdraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar was
dragged half a U.S. cent lower Friday by the downdraft from Asia
and the release of weaker-than-expected wages data.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign exchange market, the currency crisis in
neighboring regions reclaimed center stage, to overwhelm important
local wages and housing finance data.
</P>
<P>
Asian and Japanese currency weakness pressured the Australian
dollar to close at 67.31 U.S. cents, from 67.83 Thursday, with
traders fearing it will fall below 67 U.S. cents over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Bank Ltd. foreign exchange manager Mark O'Leary said
Asia concerns were presently driving the Australian dollar, as
pundits mull over the likely extent of the negative impact of the
regional crisis on the Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said full-time adult
average weekly ordinary time earnings rose 0.4 percent to 711.30
Australian dollars (478.70 U.S. dollars) in seasonally adjusted
terms in the three months to November, and 3.7 percent in the year
to November.
</P>
<P>
SBC Warburg Australia foreign exchange executive director John
Radinoff said Friday's local data were by-passed as the market
focused on offshore influences.
</P>
<P>
Radinoff said there was market speculation that the weakening
Asian currencies would smack the Australian dollar below 67 U.S.
cents in offshore trading.
</P>
<P>
As for next week, Colonial State Bank chief economist Craig
James said the main domestic hurdle for the Australian dollar
would be the Reserve Bank of Australia's quarterly assessment on
the economy, due on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The markets are looking for a realistic assessment on the
impact of the Asian crisis from the Reserve Bank," James said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 83.97 Japanese yen, from
83.63 locally Thursday, and at 1.2196 German marks, from 1.2352.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
