<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Use of S'pore Dollar for Regional Trade unrealistic: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Finance Minister
Richard Hu said Friday that it is not realistic for the Singapore
dollar to replace the U.S. dollar as the base currency for trade
among the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
countries.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a senior Singapore government official
ever commented publicly on the proposal since it was aired last
week when Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad toured several
ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after opening an information technology exhibition,
Richard Hu said that Singapore is a small economy and there are
not enough Singapore dollars to go around.
</P>
<P>
On the trade credit plan proposed by Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong, he said there has been good response.
</P>
<P>
He said that the proposed multilateral agreement of letters of
credit will supplement bilateral pacts which Indonesia has with
other parties.
</P>
<P>
As for the need for reduced government expenditure in view of
the regional currency crisis, the finance minister said that at
every budget, government departments have been asked to be prudent
with their spending in non-essential areas, and that is especially
relevant this year.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that all essential spending will carry on as
usual.  
</P>
</TEXT>
