<HEADLINE> Construction of An Amusement Facility Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda National Environment
Management Authority (NEMA) has instructed an Asian businessman
to suspend his construction of an amusement park in the south of
the capital Kampala, The New Vision reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Henry Aryamanya-Mugisha, NEMA's deputy executive director,
said they had told Sudhir Ruparelia to suspend his work in
Munyonyo, about 8 kilometers south of Kampala, until an
environmental impact assessment is carried out and his project
approved.
</P>
<P>
The official added that Ruparelia did not get the permission
for developing the place on the lakeside.
</P>
<P>
Margaret Lwanga, an official in the Ministry of Natural
Resources, said the construction of Ruparelia's amusement
facilities could destroy spawning grounds for fish and silt the
lake.
</P>
<P>
The project will enter Lake Victoria, Lwanga noted. She also
expressed worries over the disposal of wastes to be generated.
</P>
<P>
The project includes an amusement park, six tennis and six
squash courts, a club house, a restaurant and a show jumping ring
for houses. Ruparelia has imported 32 horses from South Africa
and Kenya for his project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
