<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Round-up) Maier Crashes, Dream Tournament Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Pre-race favourite Hermann
Maier of Austria crashed in the long-delayed men's downhill race on
the day when the men's ice hockey "Dream Tournament" began at the 18th
Olympic Winter Games on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the men's downhill event which had been postponed for six days,
Jean-Luc Cretier of France surprised all as well as himself to win the
showpiece title, clocking at one minute and 50.11 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Lasse Kjus of Norway was second with 4.54 seconds behind and Hames
Trinkle of Austria third at 1:50.63.
</P>
<P>
After finishing his run, Cretuer, third starter, watched the crash
of Maier, who started at the fourth place.
</P>
<P>
Maier, former bricklayer, crashed 18 seconds after the starting
gate and bounced into the air, somersaulting twice before landing on
his back in the deep snow after breaking the safety nets. Fortunately,
he only suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian, the most successful skiier in the sport with 10 World
Cup victories last season, managed to stand up and walked without
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The race was delayed by about nine minutes to repair the nets.
</P>
<P>
Italian Luca Cattaneo also crashed and had his left leg badly
injured. He was airlifted by a helicopter to a nearby hospital.
</P>
<P>
Some other skiiers also lost their balance at the same spot but did
not crash.
</P>
<P>
The downhill race witnessed 15 skiiers out of competitions.
</P>
<P>
The ice hockey tournament at winter Olympics entered into a new era
when Sweden opened the championship round game with a stunning 4-2
victory over much fancied team the United States.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that ice professionals could play in winter
Olympics. The United States, Sweden, Russia, Czech Republic, Canada
and Finland, all gold contenders, feature NHL players in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
In the men's combined event, Austrian Mario Reitter, who in the
leading place after the slalom, chalked up the title despite a sixth
finish in the combined downhill event Friday afternoon. Reitter had
an aggregated time of three minutes and 8.06 seconds for the title,
beating Kjus to the second at 3:08.65. Christian Mayer of Austria was
third at 3:10.11.
</P>
<P>
The only other gold medal of the day was decided in the men's luge
doubles event. Stefan Krausse and Jan Behrendt collected the second
gold medal for Germany in the sport with a clocking of one minute and
41.105 seconds from two runs.
</P>
<P>
The United States broke European's domination in the sport when two
pairs from the country won the silver and bronze in the men's doubles
respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 500m speed skating first race today, Canada's
Catriona LeMay-Doan set a new Olympic record 38.39 seconds, beating
the previous mark of 39.10, which Bonnie Blair of the United States
has held for 10 years since her gold-winning time in the Calgary Games
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
LeMay-Doan's record-smashing win also puts her in the lead at the
end of the first day of the two-day event.
</P>
<P>
Her teammate Susan Auch, silver medalist in Lillehammer, Norway
four years ago, took the second place, crossing the finish line in a
time of 38.42 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Japanese skater Tomomi Okazaki was third for the second race at
38.55.
</P>
<P>
After seven-day competitions, Germany jumped to the leading place
in the medal table, with five golds, four silvers and four bronzes.
Russia was second at four golds and three silvers. Norway was standing
at third with three golds, five silvers and three bronzes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
