<HEADLINE> Price Cut to Make Home-Made Cars More Competitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The price for Jetta standard
model cars manufactured by a major Chinese automaker was recently
reduced to under 120,000 yuan, which conforms with the
international market.
</P>
<P>
According to industry sources, this is the result of
cost-reduction efforts made by the First Automotive
Works-Volkswagen. And the price cut is considered a major step
toward China's acceptance into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The price of the Jetta was slashed by 12.8 percent. This is a
follow-up to the price reduction on Santana cars produced by
Shanghai Automotive Industry Corp.
</P>
<P>
Santana is now as low as 114,000 yuan after its price was
lowered by 20,000 yuan early this year.
</P>
<P>
During the week before the Chinese lunar new year (Jan. 28),
more than 600 Santana cars were sold in the largest Santana outlet
in Beijing, according to Hu Jiabin, general manager of the
company.
</P>
<P>
Hu, Santana's general agent in North China, said the company
sold only 100 Santanas during the same period in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the price cuts for the Santana and Jetta, some Citroen
1.3 model cars had already been lowered to 118,000 yuan, and
further reductions are expected.
</P>
<P>
The slashes are expected to trigger price changes in other
brands such as Xiali.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that with expanding production and lower costs,
Chinese-made cars are not likely to be severely affected by the
country's tariff reduction.
</P>
<P>
The current tariff levied on mid-level to luxury cars has been
reduced from 120 percent to 100 percent. For mid-level to
inexpensive cars, it has been lowered from 100 percent to 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 481,600 cars were produced in China, of which 474,200
were sold. The production and sales volumes of Santana cars ranked
first, with 230,000 rolling off the assembly lines last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
