<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Percent World Bank Projects Fail to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- About 40 percent of the World
Bank projects failed to meet their objects, a bank official has
said.
</P>
<P>
Randolph Harris, World Bank resident representative to Uganda,
told a journalism workshop Thursday that one reason of the
failure is that the projects did not involve the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
He gave examples in agricultural sector, saying "some of the
farmers who were supposed to produce for export did not get the
money, so they ended up not producing the crops."
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the failure is the suspension of the
institutions concerned to carry out their schemes.
</P>
<P>
"In the past a separate implementation unit was established
with the support from World Bank or other institutions, so when
donor funding was stopped, the unit disappeared," Randolph noted.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank currently emphasizes capacity building in its
projects, he said, adding "Today through capacity building for
people and institutions, the beneficiaries are able to make
projects sustainable."
</P>
<P>
The workshop was organised by the Norwegian government and
Economic Development Institute of the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
