<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Pudong Plans New Measures for Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Pudong New Area of
Shanghai this year will take new measures to promote its economic
and trade ties with other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
A major measure is to launch another Sino-overseas foreign
trade company and strive to win approval from the central
authorities to allow more trade companies from other parts of
China to set up subsidiaries in Pudong, a rising financial and
trade district separated from downtown Shanghai by the
Huangpujiang River.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou Hongli, deputy director of Shanghai Municipal
Economic and Trade Commission, China last year allowed the
establishment of joint-venture foreign trade firms in Pudong on a
trial basis. Currently there are three Sino-overseas joint-venture
trade firms in Pudong.
</P>
<P>
Starting the first quarter of this year Shanghai will implement
new customs practices in Pudong to support a new round of
infrastructure construction in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Waigaoqiao Bonded Zone of Pudong will be the apple of the
eye in Pudong's new effort for economic and trade growth.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, there were 261 processing enterprises in
the bonded zone, where many multinational corporations and
enterprise groups have established regional or national
distribution centers for manufactured products and components.
</P>
<P>
Pudong's foreign trade volume grew 22.6 percent to 9.9 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997, with exports standing at 4.6 billion U.S.
dollars, according to figures from the Shanghai Customs Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
