<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from countries of the Middle East:
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Preparations are under way in the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) for a new nationwide subscription for the shares of a
Dubai-seated industrial company for central cooling systems.
</P>
<P>
Officials and businessmen in Abu Dhabi and Dubai are busy
fulfilling the establishment procedures with a capital of
approximately 136 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The central cooling company will offer 55 percent of its paid
capital for general subscription among UAE citizens.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The General Telecommunications Foundation in Syria
has lowered the prices of telephone receivers by 33 percent, and
the cost of the immediate installation of a telephone will be
reduced to 1000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the costs and tariffs of telephone services have also
been lowered for the second time in the last five months. This is
attributed to "intensive competition" despite the fact that no
other company is engaged in this sector which is a monopoly of the
public sector in Syria.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A Jordanian banking source anticipates that the
Palestinian Aqsa Islamic Bank will commence its works in the
territories under Palestinian National Authority control in mid
1998.
</P>
<P>
According to Moussa Shehata, general manager of the Jordanian
Islamic Bank which owns a large share in the new bank, the
Palestinian Aqsa Islamic bank will focus on banking, investment
and financing activities.
