<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Officers Enthusiastic about Higher Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Major Wang Jing hasn't had a
weekend off for six months. Each weekend, the Chinese Air Force
officer goes to the Air Force Command Institute to study in a
graduate program.
</P>
<P>
On weekdays, Wang works in the General Hospital of the Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
"It has been hard work, but I'm determined to complete the
three-year program," she said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, more Chinese army officers are receiving higher
education while keeping their jobs.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 officers participated in graduate and
undergraduate programs last year, according to the General
Political Department of the People's Liberation Army (PLA), and
nearly 150,000 have received higher education diplomas since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Young officers account for a large part of those in
undergraduate and graduate programs, said Gen. Wang Zhenkai, dean
of studies at the Air Force Command Institute.
</P>
<P>
The rising enthusiasm for higher education is closely related
to the development of the Chinese army, said military experts.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, many officers have become acutely aware of
their deficiencies in knowledge and competence when weaponry has
been much improved, they explain, and the fact that officers who
have received higher education tend to get promoted more than
others.
</P>
<P>
China's education authorities and the military have encouraged
officers to continue their education while keeping their jobs.
</P>
<P>
More education for military officers will contribute to the
improvement of the officers' corps. Some 62.5 percent of Chinese
army officers have had college education, up from 22.2 percent in
1988.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
