<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Transport Business Gaining Speed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- High speed is becoming a sign
of the times on China's highways, railways and navigable waterways.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Communications show that China
now has 4,735 kilometers (km) of expressways, compared with only
500 km in the early 1990s. In 1998, the country plans to add 800
km of expressways and 540 km of fast roads for the use of
automobiles only.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the country's first expressway, from
Shenyang to Dalian in northeast China's Liaoning Province, started
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Feasibility research into an express railway from Beijing to
Shanghai, the two largest cities in China, is being speeded
up. The designed speed for the road is expected to reach 250 km
per hour, 50 km more than the international express standard,
making the entire journey 6.5 hours long, according to sources
from the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
A quasi-express railway linking Guangzhou with Shenzhen in
south China's Guangdong Province, has already gone into operation,
with a speed of 160 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the train speed was raised on a general basis on
last April 1. On the three trunk lines of Beijing-Guangzhou,
Beijing-Shanghai and Beijing-Harbin, trains now run at a speed of
140 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
The China State Shipbuilding Corp. says that more than 200
high-performance vehicles are operating on more than 70 water
routes on the Zhujiang (Pearl River), Yangtze, Huanghe (Yellow),
and Heilongjiang rivers as well as Bohai Bay and the Yellow, East
china and South China seas. These ships cruise at 60 to 70 km per
hour.
</P>
<P>
Air transport, with high speed as its advantage, is
continuously increasing. Latest statistics from the Civil Aviation
Administration of China show that airplanes carried 56.3 million
passengers last year, still up from 1995, when the figure
surpassed 50 million for the first time.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.25 million tons of cargo was mailed via air last
year, up 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
