<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sticks to Deadline for Mergers of Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
will stick to its original deadline of March 31 for local
financial institutions to announce their merger plans, Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We will stick to the planned date for mergers among financial
institutions," Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said at a
press conference after the inauguration of a mobile phone factory
in Shah Alam near here.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government has decided to encourage local
financial institutions to merge into bigger entities to
efficiently face the onslaught of greater competition when the
local financial services sector is opened up to foreign
institutions in the future.
</P>
<P>
There are 35 local financial institutions in the country and
the government has planned to get them merged into 5 to 7 bigger
entities by the deadline.
</P>
<P>
It is of paramount importance to do so, Anwar said, adding "I
think the macroeconomic policy consideration is determined partly
by strong financial institutions."
</P>
<P>
Anwar said Malaysia had adjusted its fiscal policies and even
took unpopular measures to ensure that the macro-economic
stabilization process was uninterrupted and that there was viable
economic development.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue effective monitoring and surveillance to
ensure that our plans, including the moderation of credit growth
will be observed, whatever difficulties that we may encounter," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister also said Malaysia would not consider to
establish a currency board system "because the ringgit has been
strengthening in last three weeks."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
