<HEADLINE> Share Prices Down Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined
sharply on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) plunged by 47.6 points to end at 1,552.69
points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that share prices went down after a bout of
profit-taking, spurred by Indonesia-linked concerns. As a result,
the STII shed almost three percent.
</P>
<P>
This was the second straight day of losses for the local
bourse, they said, noting that the initial reaction was in
response to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) concerns over
Indonesia implementing a currency board.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume stood at 859.98 million units, valued
at 798.62 million Singapore dollars (about 481.1 million US
dollars). Declines led advances by 206 to 171, while 234 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 126.01 million units. It was followed by
Rekapac which had 75.63 million shares traded. M. Resources was
next with 50.99 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it surged by 5.9 dollars to finish at 36.5 Singapore
dollars. Bukit Sembawang rose by 15 cents to end at 9.8 Singapore
dollars. NBT increased by 14 cents to close at 4.14 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) Foreign was the
biggest loser as it declined by 1.2 dollars to end at 23.7
Singapore dollars. DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign
fell by 80 cents to close at 12.9 Singapore dollars, while C&AMP;C
(Cycle &AMP; Carriage) lost 55 cents to finish at 6.95 Singapore
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
