<HEADLINE> Nigerian Traditional Rulers Ask Abacha to Run for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's traditional rulers
have joined the call for the head of the military government,
General Sani Abacha to run for the civilian presidency in the
coming elections.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with Abacha Thursday in the national capital
Abuja, the traditional rulers said, "We have carefully looked
round and with all humility hasten to say that you are the person
fully qualified to occupy the seat."
</P>
<P>
"The entire membership of the traditional rulers forum has,
therefore, decided to humbly but strongly appeal to you to
consider contesting the post of civilian president in the 1998
elections so that you can continue with the good work you have
been doing," said a statement read by Alhaji Mohammadu Maccido,
the sultan of Sokoto.
</P>
<P>
The traditional rulers said they are making this appeal "with
every sense of responsibility and patriotism, firmly believing
that it will be in the overall interest of peace, unity,
stability and prosperity of the nation".
</P>
<P>
Abacha, in reaction, was quoted by local media as saying that
the call by traditional rulers is a recognition of his
administration's efforts to improve the lot of Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the increasing call on him to run as "a
challenge" and said he needs divine guidance to make the right
choice, reports said.
</P>
<P>
As Nigeria's transition to civil rule program draws to the
end, there have been increasing calls on Abacha to shed his
uniform and contest for the civilian presidency in August.
</P>
<P>
The join-in of traditional rulers, who are very influential in
decision-making in Nigeria, is believed to be a strong
reinforcement to the already powerful persuasion campaign.
</P>
<P>
Just on Tuesday, leaders of Nigeria's five political parties
also met with Abacha in Abuja to discuss key issues concerning
the transition program.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said the parties discussed the issue of their
adopting Abacha as their consensus candidate, but that has been
denied by the party leaders.
</P>
<P>
One thing is certain now, that is, less than six months to the
presidential election, only one aspirant has appeared and he has
not been adopted by any of the parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
