<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Farmer Discovers 4,000-year-old Spades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A farmer in Yongning county in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region recently unearthed
two stone tools shaped like shovels when he was ploughing on a
hillside near his village of Minzheng.
</P>
<P>
The villager, Chen Songrong, says he found the two tools in
about 30 cm of earth. Local archaeologists say the two shovels
belong to the New Stone Age and are about 4,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
One of them was 30.7 cm by 16 cm and 1 cm thick and in good
condition, but the other was incomplete and 34.7 cm by 15.7 cm
wide by 1.2 cm.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists explain that the tools were a kind of farm
implement from the later years of the New Stone Age and are
helpful in the study of primitive agriculture in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
