<HEADLINE> S. African Budget Deficit Rises to 4.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government has increased its spending estimate by 2.73 billion
Rand (550 million U.S. Dollars) and accordingly revised its
budget deficit to 4.3 percent, South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted Finance Minister Trevor Manuel as saying that the
revised deficit was better than the 4.5 percent expected by the
markets, but was 0.3 percentage points higher than planned.
</P>
<P>
Total budgeted spending for the year would now amount to
189.47 billion Rand (38.3 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Unveiling his budget adjustments in the National Assembly in
Cape Town, Manuel said the overspending could roughly be broken
down into two components.
</P>
<P>
About 1.5 billion Rand (about 305 million Dollars) of it would
go toward the financially troubled provinces, while the remaining
1.2 billion (245 million Dollars) pertained to roll-overs or
unspent funds from the previous financial year.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product has been revised down from 622 billion
Rand (126 billion Dollars) to 613 billion Rand (124 billion
Dollars), and the higher deficit was based on the lower number,
Manuel told a media briefing.
</P>
<P>
However, revenue collection figures were on target,
notwithstanding the lower economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
