<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Troops Urged to Speed up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 13 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise has expressed his concern at the low pace of
transformation in national armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on Thursday, Modise said the
equal opportunity and affirmative action programs would be
accelerated to enhance the legitimacy of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The minister was concerned about the low progress in the
defense force towards reflecting the country's diversity. Only
22.5 percent of defense force officers were black and only 11 out
of more than 50 generals were black, he said.
</P>
<P>
There had to be progress in transforming the force because
unless it became fully representative people would not accept it,
Modise noted.
</P>
<P>
On troops change, Modise said the number of general officers
would be cut as the force downsized. Downsizing would be
achieved through natural attribution, intergovernmental
transfers, non-renewal of short-term contracts, voluntary
severance packages and retrenchment.
</P>
<P>
Draft plans for downsizing of the defense force from current
94,000 members to 70,000 over three years and the merging of
units were reportedly to be presented to the Defense Ministry
next month.
</P>
<P>
Rationalization was set to begin at the end of the year, but
the process would be spread over several years, the ministry's
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Modise said the mergers could allow the defense force to
concentrate resources to help the police and to acquire capital
equipment. Only 13 percent of the present budget went to capital
cost, and restructuring would allow this to rise to 30 percent
over the three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
