<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ice Hockey Federation Seeks Co-operation with NHL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The president of the
International Ice Hockey Federaton (IIHF) Rene Fasel said on Friday
that it would be beneficial if there was some co-operation between the
National Hockey League (NHL) and the world governing body of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
He made the comment in response to concern the fact that Belarus
defenseman Ruslan Salie and American team's Gary Suter both played in
Nagano games despite NHL suspensions.
</P>
<P>
Team Canada star Paul Kariya will not be able to compete in Nagano
due to injuries sustained from the body-check that led to Suter's
NHL's suspension.
</P>
<P>
"I think that will be a matter of discussion in the next
negotiation," Fasel told a press conference at the Big Hat ice arena.
</P>
<P>
"We had a lot of discussion and problems to find together here. I
think maybe we didn't spead enough about that," Fasel added.
</P>
<P>
The president said that opposite cases have happened as well, when
players from Europe, who are members of the IIHF, are suspended on the
international level and go to play at the NHL where the suspensions do
not apply.
</P>
<P>
He also said that during the ice hockey tournament a team may be
disqualified if member players test positive, but he left the door
open for discussion.
</P>
<P>
"We will follow the rules of the IOC (International Olympic
Committee) and also of the rules of the International Ice Hockey
Federation."
</P>
<P>
But Fasel added that before any action is taken, there will be
discussion and possibly flexibility.
</P>
<P>
"If we have a positive test, we will sit together with the IOC, the
medical commission, and the juridical commission and handle this
case," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
