<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Growth Rate Causes Environment Degradation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- High population growth rate
has caused enviroment degradation in Uganda, the National
Environment Management Authority (NEMA) said in its biannual
report.
</P>
<P>
An increasing demand for food and charcoal as energy source in
the country without sufficient investment into agriculture forces
farmers to expand their cultivation land, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Without means to invest in intensive agriculture, households
are increasingly encroaching on marginal lands which cannot
support agriculture sustainably," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Expansion of agricultural land often leads to depletion of
wetland and encroachment of forest reserves and wildlife areas,
the New Vision quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indiscriminate felling of trees is blamed for reduction in
water catchment areas, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has rich water energy. But high electricity cost forces
its residents to rely on charcoal. The price of charcoal is half
of its equivelent of electricity, an earlier report said. For a
family of four or five, a monthly charcoal fee for cooking is
some 15,000 Uganda Shillings (some 14 U.S. dollars), while a
salary of an average skilled worker in Kampala is some 70,000
Uganda Shillings (some 65 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
