<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economies to Recover in 3 Years: Australian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer predicted Friday that Asian economies would
recover within three years if the world avoided making serious
blunders that hindered their comeback.
</P>
<P>
In his address to business students at the University of South
Australia in the Australian coastal city of Adelaide, Downer said
that "If the world avoids making any serious mistakes in the next
year, then the Asian economic crisis will work through over two to
three years."
</P>
<P>
Downer also urged Australian firms to take up opportunities
presented by the economic crisis, such as cheaper assets, warning
that if they did not stick with Asia while it worked through its
problems, they would find it harder to get back into re-emerging
Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
"Australian firms should take the opportunities that are
presented because ... my judgment is that within the next two to
three years, Asian economies will be back on the path to growth,"
he was quoted by the Australian Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I think businesses that walk away from Asia now will find it a
lot more difficult to get back in."
</P>
<P>
Downer said the International Monetary Fund packages to bail
out Indonesia, Thailand and South Korea must be fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the resurgence of neo-protectionism should also be
avoided, particularly by the United States, which should continue
to allow Asian access to its markets.
</P>
<P>
Downer also revealed the Australian government was holding
talks with Thai officials about whether Australia should provide
more aid money to help address the social problems that will
result from the financial crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Invests 7.87 Billion Dollars in Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh invested a total of
362.34 billion taka (about 7.87 billion U.S. dollars) in the
industrial sector during the last seven fiscal years, the national
news agency BSS reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael
Ahmed in the Parliament Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken up necessary measures for increasing
the volume of investment in the country, including exemption of
income tax for the local investors, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government has also taken some measures for
encouraging foreign investors, such as ensuring equal behavior to
local and foreign investment, protecting foreign investment from
nationalization, ensuring proper repatriation of the sale of
shares and profit of investment, ensuring 100 percent foreign
investment and setting up export processing zones in the private
section, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has signed bilateral agreements with 19 countries
for the protection and development of capital investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Due to the large amount of investments, Bangladesh's industrial
sector has grown steadily in the past seven fiscal years though
the growth rate is not as high as expected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
