<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1700 GMT, February 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Qiao Shi, chairman of the Standing Committee of
China's National People's Congress (NPC), said Friday that he was
impressed by the rapid infrastructural development in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Qiao and his wife Yu Wen visited infrastructure projects here
Friday morning in the company of Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa and his wife Betty
Tung. (Hong Kong-Qiao Shi-Tour)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The World Health Organization (WHO) and Kenya's
Health Ministry have sounded alert to medical personnel and
Nairobi residents over possible outbreak of the Rift Valley Fever
in the capital city of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The fast killing fever first emerged in the North Eastern
Province two months ago and has been making a steady spread
westwards and has lately been reported in Kajiado and Kiambu
districts neighboring Nairobi, Kenya Times reported Friday.
(Kenya-killer disease)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Forensic experts have so far identified only 10
victims who perished in the crash of Cebu Pacific Air Flight 387
in the southern Philippines 12 days ago.
</P>
<P>
This was released Friday by Jesus Dureza, head of the
Presidential Action Center which coordinates the search and
retrieval operations of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Dureza said the bodies of the victims were already claimed one
after the other by their relatives as of Thursday. The process of
identification is still undergoing. (Philippines-Air Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- Prime Minister Jenny Shipley said Friday that
New Zealand would like to see its relations with China deepen in
all areas, including the field of defense.
</P>
<P>
She made the remark when meeting visiting Chinese Defense
Minister General Chi Haotian. (New Zealand-China-Chi)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley
indicated on Friday that her country favors a peaceful solution to
the issue concerning United Nations weapon inspectors in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone discussion with U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday morning, Shipley emphasized to Clinton New Zealand's
position that every diplomatic effort should be made, including
through the UN, to achieve a peaceful outcome, according to a
press statement from the Prime Minister's Office. (New
Zealand-Iraq-Resolution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev Thursday
reiterated his country's opposition to military strikes against
Iraq, and categorically denied that Russia had negotiated the sale
of equipment to Iraq to make proscribed weapons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference with U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen, Sergeyev stressed that Iraq must comply with
U.N. resolutions, but compliance should be achieved only through
diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
He said if the U.S. turned to force to settle the Iraqi
crisis, it would hurt and set back bilateral ties between Russia
and the U.S. (Russia-Defense-Minister Iraq) 
</P>
