<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Fish Output Nearly Doubles Since 1970: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) Friday said that some 30 million
fishers around the world produced 116 million tons of fish in
1997, up sharply from 65 million tons in 1970.
</P>
<P>
"The growth is mainly related to the increase in the size of
fishing fleets and the expansion of aquaculture," according to a
new survey by the FAO available here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The number of fishers in 1997 also increased by 130 percent
compared with 1970 and 95 percent of the fishers are from
developing countries, the FAO said.
</P>
<P>
The organization also said that in 1997, about 85 percent of
the fishers in the world are in Asia, mainly in China, India,
Vietnam, Indonesia, Bangladesh and the Philippines, compared with
77 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
The number of fishers in north and central America also
increased, reaching some 840,000 in 1990, but in Europe the figure
dropped markedly to 390,000 in 1990, the FAO said.
</P>
<P>
"Fishery labor productivity and capital intensity vary widely
among countries. Highly industrialized fisheries generally employ
few fishers per unit of output," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Rome-based UN body also warned that many fishery resources
are overexploited and declining, indicating about 35 percent of
the 200 major marine fish resources are showing declining yields.
</P>
<P>
It notes that a drastic reduction of at least 30 percent of
world fishing capacity is needed to rebuild overfished resources.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> San Francisco Leads U.S. Cities in Housing Market Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 12 (Xinhua) -- San Francisco has the most
expensive housing market in the United States, according to data
released earlier this week by a real estate association.
</P>
<P>
The average price for a home in San Francisco for the fourth
quarter of 1997 was 304,600 U.S. dollars, edging out Honolulu's
300,000 dollars, reported the California Association of Realtors
(CAR).
</P>
<P>
The last time when San Francisco was at the peak of the housing
market was the second quarter of 1989. That year the median price
for a home was 266,500 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The recovery in the San Francisco housing market last year was
isolated. In fact, CAR said the prices in cities throughout the
region jumped as the economic boom, fueled by Silicon Valley,
rolled on.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, home sales increased 3.1 percent and the median
home price rose five percent to 128,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
In California, an existing, single-family detached home in 1997
was 186,490 dollars, up 5.2 percent from 177,270 dollars a year
ago -- the sharpest increase since 1989. The state sold 555,380
homes last year, up 9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The median price of 316,250 dollars of Santa Clara County,
where Silicon Valley is located, was the highest among 16 regions.
</P>
<P>
An earlier CAR report said that in California, 39 percent of
households can afford to buy the median-priced homes. But this
masks regional differences of housing affordability. In some areas,
new home building was not necessarily taking place where it was
most needed.
</P>
<P>
The high cost of housing should trigger more house construction
since it often signals housing shortages, but this was not always
the case, CAR said. This perhaps constitutes part of the reason
for housing price hikes in, for instance, San Francisco Bay Area,
where affordability is significantly below the statewide norm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
