<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Currency Crisis to End in 9 Months: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine currency crisis
could end in nine months' time owing to the strong economic
fundamentals of the country, an economist predicted Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jesus P. Estanislao, dean of the Asian Development Bank
Institute in Tokyo, told reporters here that the road to recovery
is likely to be attained by the Philippines soon.
</P>
<P>
Based on the positive developments that are taking place in the
market, the Philippine economy is moving towards relative
stability among the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
countries in the short term, he said.
</P>
<P>
Estanislao urged the ASEAN economies affected by the turmoil to
put up a monitoring mechanism to ensure greater coordination on
exchange rates and other macro-economic financial variables.
</P>
<P>
"They will have to draw the line firmly against competitive
devaluation in the region. Then they will have to wake up to the
fact that as their trade and investment regimes continue to open
up more freely towards each other, there is no escaping from the
need for more open consultation and closer coordination on
macro-economic fundamentals," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Estanislao also urged the affected economies to modernize their
financial systems, saying this should not be limited to the
development of the capital markets.
</P>
<P>
"Even more basic is the attention that must be focused on the
banking systems, which need to adopt best practices of supervision
and regulation, disclosure and competition, administration and the
setting of standards in line with more open market systems," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
