<HEADLINE> Lemay-Doan Leads Women's 500m Speed Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 13 (Xinhua) -- World record holder Catriona
Lemay-Doan set up her title position for Saturday's Olympic women's
500-meter speed skating as she won the first of two-run race in Nagano
"M-Wave" rink Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian, who set the world record of 37.55 seconds in Calgary
on December 28 in 1997, finished first in 38.39 seconds to improve the
Games record by 0.71 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The old Games mark was set by former American superstar Bonie
Kathleen Blair on February 22 in Calgary in 1988.
</P>
<P>
All other five of first six-finishing skaters surpassed the Blair's
Games record before Saturday's second and final run race.
</P>
<P>
Lemay-Doan's teammate Susan Auch, silver medalist in Lillehammer
four years ago, ranked second with a time of 38.42 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Auch was followed by two Japanese Tomomi Okazaki in 38.55 and Kyoko
Shimazaki in 38.75.
</P>
<P>
Franziska Schenk of Germany, who took the bronze at the Lillehammer
Games, finished fifth in 38.88 seconds. American Christine Witty came
in sixth by clocking 39.09.
</P>
<P>
China's best Xu Ruihong, who took fourth with a time of 39.54 in
Lillehammer, skated 39.49 seconds, placing 13th of 37 skaters.
</P>
<P>
It was disappointed for Xu's teammate Wang Manli, who was hindered
at the crossing straight by Austrian Emese Hunyady. Wang skated well
in the first 390 meters and finally managed to finish in 40.01 seconds
for 22nd place.
</P>
<P>
Hunyady was disqualified because of hindering Wang, officials said
after the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
