<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicle Sales Drop Sharply in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- New vehicle sales hit their
lowest ebb in Kenya since the currency and inflation crisis of
1994, the East African Standard newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Motor Industry Association (KMI) recorded 838 sales
-- a drop of more than 35 percent on last year's monthly
averages, and the worst single month since October 1994 when only
522 units were sold.
</P>
<P>
The sector is geared to selling 1,000 units per month or more.
</P>
<P>
"January was an across-the-board downturn," said the KMI
Bureau, acknowledging that January's figures reflected a
generally unhappy and uncertain business picture.
</P>
<P>
"At this stage the industry is treating it as just a very
rough month, resulting from a combination of negative influences
-- not only a grim economic outlook but also other seasonal
factors such as the weather, unresolved political issues and cash
flow pressures on buyers facing a lot of start-of-year bills," it
said.
</P>
<P>
"No doom or boom conclusions can ever be drawn from a single
month. Cash flow positions should ease during February and there
will be a major promotional push in March and working hard for a
recovery," said the bureau.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of March we will know to what extent today's
figures are just a bad patch, or a prognosis," it concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
