<HEADLINE> Malawi's Sole University in Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Malawi's sole university, the
University of Malawi, may be forced to close because of financial
crisis, The Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian newspaper quoted Africa Information Afrique as
reporting that the government has not yet provided 3.5 million
U.S. Dollars for the university to run up to March.
</P>
<P>
"The government has just kept quiet on the money requested.
From the look of things there is no sign that the government is
going to give us money," Africa Information Afrique quoted the
university's acting Finance Officer Yafat Malunga as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 1997/98 budget allocated 17 million dollars but the
government has only released 10 million dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are unable to pay monthly house rents, retirement
benefits, maintenance bills, administrating first-year entrance
exams as well as passage of expatriate staff," he said.
</P>
<P>
The academic year which was supposed to start in January has
been pushed to April. Last year the university opened seven
months late following a strike by lecturers who were demanding a
salary hike.
</P>
<P>
Malunga said the university owes the lecturers 446,000 dollars
in salary arrears following the 50 percent salary increase last
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
