<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- A police station in Zambia's
Western Province was raided and set on fire Monday evening and
some weapons were stolen, Zambia Daily Mail reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a statement issued by the police Thursday
evening as saying that the police station in Limulunga, a town
540 kilometers west of Lusaka, was raided by gangsters at 21
hours and the criminal investigation department was set on fire.
</P>
<P>
Some weapons including an AK 47 automatic rifle, three 303
rifles, a pistol and an undisclosed number of rounds of
ammunition were stolen during the raid, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
But police in a swift move cornered and shot dead one of the
suspected gangsters while another one sustained injuries.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted the Inspector-General of Police Francis
Ndhlovu as saying Thursday that four police officers were injured
in the shoot out.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that some exhibits, furniture and other documents
were destroyed in the fire which damaged half of the building.
</P>
<P>
Three suspects from the group escaped and the police have
launched a man hunt for the trio whom Ndhlovu described as
"dangerous".
</P>
<P>
Investigation into the arson and shooting have been
instituted, according to the police officer. 
