<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer Disease Looms in Kenyan Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) and Kenya's Health Ministry have sounded alert to medical
personnel and Nairobi residents over possible outbreak of the
Rift Valley Fever in the capital city of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The fast killing fever first emerged in the North Eastern
Province two months ago and has been making a steady spread
westwards and has lately been reported in Kajiado and Kiambu
districts neighboring Nairobi, Kenya Times reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The threat of an outbreak is looming as a result of Nairobi's
central position at a network of major roads, especially from the
east and south where the deadly disease has been reported among
the Somali, Borana and Maasai pastoral communities.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi's meat supply originates largely from the Maasai
districts of Narok and Kajiado and also from North Eastern
Province.
</P>
<P>
Meat and other animal products are major conduits for the
deadly virus causing the disease to the human species, which also
attacks and kills animals in 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
Medical personnel have been directed to be on the watchout for
the symptoms of the disease among incoming patients and to submit
fluid specimen from victims to the Africa Medical and Research
Foundation if and when they come across any.
</P>
<P>
However, so far no incident of the disease has been diagnosed
in the city, said Dr Mary Wangai, the Nairobi Provincial Medical
Officer of Health.
</P>
<P>
The medical staff are being briefed on preventive and
management measures including the wearing of gloves, masks and
other protective clothing to prevent against bodily contact with
body fluids of infected victims.
</P>
<P>
All workers at slaughterhouses are to adopt similar measures
and Ministry of Health is to improve surveillance on all meat,
milk and animal products.
</P>
<P>
The city dwellers have been advised to avoid the consumption
of improperly cooked meat and meat products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0192 </DOCNO>
