<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Proposes Framework on E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia proposed Friday
the setting up of an ASEAN framework on Electronic Commerce
(E-Commerce) to provide the platform for a collective vision of
the emerging digital market place.
</P>
<P>
Such a regional initiative may be necessary to address the
prevalent issues brought about by the rapidly advancing "digital
economy" and E-Commerce, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
said at the opening of the Roundtable on Electronic Communities in
Asia here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The framework would also provide the basis for discussions to
facilitate the development of an ASEAN position to catalyze the
growth of E-Commerce, Mahathir said, who reiterated his
government's commitment to support the growth of E-Commerce.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said although the growth of E-Commerce was essentially
private-sector driven, there was a need to monitor and regulate
its development to create the right environment for E-Commerce to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
Citing Malaysia's experience, he said Malaysia has developed an
Information Technology Agenda to support the country's vision to
become a fully-developed nation by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
"We'd like to invite our ASEAN neighbors as well as everyone
interested in ironing out possible wrinkles in the progress
towards the electronic world to join us in this endeavor," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said countries with established infrastructure to support
E-Commerce in terms of human resource and quantity of service
suppliers, as well as a bigger market share and better access to
the market, would have an edge over the others.
</P>
<P>
"However, the opportunity to develop E-Commerce also presents
itself to other countries in the ASEAN region which are in a good
position to leapfrog into the information age," he said.
</P>
<P>
Developments in E-Commerce spawn many related issues which
challenge common and established practices, laws and systems, he
said, adding that with this new digital economy, business
activities would be possible with minimal physical movement of
people, money and in many cases, products.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said many of the existing rules in today's economy
could no longer be applied in the digital economy.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the fundamental requirement for the successful
take-off of E-Commerce was trust and the guarantee that
transactions can take place safely and securely.
</P>
<P>
"It is therefore imperative to develop a proper system of
governance to manage this movement of information - and
knowledge-based resources with the growth of electronic commerce
globally," Mahathir said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
