<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Becoming Publishing Center Of Collections Of Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Publishing houses in China's
largest commercial center have turned to printing collections of
documents in recent years.
</P>
<P>
At the upper end of the scale is the six-volume "Russian
Collection of Dunhuang Art Works", which was published by Shanghai
Classics Publishing House. It contains pictures of Buddhist
statues and frescoes, and copies of valuable manuscripts taken
from the Dunhuang grottos in northwest China's Gansu Province by a
group of Russians, 84 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The publishing house has also printed a 30-volume book of
documents on the city's land deeds issued to people from 17
nations who were doing business or living in Shanghai from 1847 to
1930.
</P>
<P>
A number of local publishing houses have also reproduced a wide
range of documents on Chinese cultural history, traditional
housing, ancient clothing and ornaments, and modern scientific
works. 
</P>
</TEXT>
