<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Coach Stuns Chinese with Blunt Comments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- His smile is genial, but his
words are blunt.
</P>
<P>
"You are playing basketball, but you are no professional
basketballers," LeRoy M. Porter, the first-ever American invited
to coach a Chinese national basketball team, told his new charges
after watching their training session.
</P>
<P>
Porter, a former NCAA coach who holds a doctor degree in
philosophy, arrived last month at a training camp for the Chinese
under-20 women's team based in southern Chinese city Liuzhou. He
was also invited as adviser to the Chinese women's senior team
bound for the the world championship in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The American coach was unhappy with skills of his students.
</P>
<P>
"They worked hard even to do something very simple," he told
reporters here after he stayed with the team for a month.
</P>
<P>
In Liuzhou, Porter had to start his drilling session from
basketball basics.
</P>
<P>
"I taught them as though I was teaching children," said Porter,
who have four-year coaching experience in NCAA Championships in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I spent first two weeks on fundamentals to bring in backups so
that we were all speaking the same basketball language," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Porter did not blame the players. "The players have passed
the coaching. The Chinese coaching is behind the players," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese basketball official Kuang Lubin said that "Porter
didn't train the players only, he trained coaches as well."
</P>
<P>
China is desperate to improve its coaching level after its
national teams played poorly in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese men's national team, 10-time Asian champion, was
dethroned by South Korea in the Asian Championships in Riyadh and
thus lost the World Championship berth in Athens in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Their women counterparts, Asian champions for four straight
times, barely made the world championships after finishing behind
South Korea and Japan in the Asian championships.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese under-20 team are good at offence, but they have
no concept of team defence," Porter said. "I don't think any team
can win without knowing the importance of team defence."
</P>
<P>
Porter, who called himself a defence coach, said the Chinese
national senior teams had the same problem.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese under-20 team will compete in the Asian Youth
Championships in September.
</P>
<P>
"I was pleased to see big improvement when I left," Porter said
early this week. He headed home in Los Angles on Wednesday after
completing one-month coaching in Liuzhou.
</P>
<P>
"They changed and became players. They just move to another
level. They are not super yet, they're on the way," Porter added.
</P>
<P>
Porter's worry remains.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he was afraid these players might forget
what he taught them. "They are smart. They learn fast, but forget
fast," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
