<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Border Village Benefiting From Peaceful Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 40 relatives of a
farmer, Huang Ruiqi, came over from Vietnam for the wedding of his
daughter in the small city of Pingxiang in south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, on the eve of the Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
This was one of the dramatic changes that have taken place in
the border village since the normalization of Sino-Vietnamese
relations in 1992. One village official who was present at the
wedding, Yu Shengchun, said, "We are very happy to have a better
life thanks to the peaceful atmosphere along the border."
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the village of 2,167 people, which was plagued by
border conflicts and mines before 1992, lived fairly poor lives in
the past. But, by last year, they were making 2,310 yuan per
capita, a higher income than the regional or national average.
</P>
<P>
Pingxiang was given approval by the state in 1992 to open to
the outside world, and border trade took off. Now, 80 percent of
the households have something to do with the business, and more
than two-thirds of the labor force are involved in it.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, China began to remove the mines that were left in the
mountains near the village, so, local farmers could plant grain
and fruits there, and the results have been good. One farmer,
Huang Jian'an, earned more than 10,000 yuan in this way in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Villagers on both sides of the border are getting along quite
well, and it is not uncommon for them to intermarry. In recent
years, more than 100 Vietnamese women have married people from the
village, and half the village people have relatives in Vietnam, Yu
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convention Supports Australia Becoming Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia's two-week long
Constitutional Convention ended Friday after endorsing a
republican model with a president to be chosen by parliament,
paving the way for a referendum in 1999 on whether and when the
country will become a republic.
</P>
<P>
A resolution in favor of the model was passed with 73 votes to
57, with 22 delegates abstaining.
</P>
<P>
The result fell four votes short of an absolute majority of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard said he accepted the
result as a clear view in favor of a particular republican model.
</P>
<P>
"The only common sense interpretation of this convention is,
firstly, that a majority of people have voted generically in favor
of a republic," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, that amongst the republican models the one that has
just got 73 votes is clearly preferred.
</P>
<P>
"Now, when you bind those two together it would be a travesty
in common sense terms of Australian democracy for that proposition
not to be put to the Australian people."
</P>
<P>
Howard has yet to decide exactly when the referendum will be
held.
</P>
<P>
The convention earlier Friday voted 89 to 52 in favor of
Australia becoming a republic, with 11 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Howard, who had promised that he would take any clearly
preferred view to a referendum, repeated his support for the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
"I honestly do not think Australia will be a better country if
we abandon the present constitutional system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he did not support the present system out of
nostalgia for a British past or for the singing of God Save the
Queen, but because an accident of history had given a coherent and
stable system of government.
</P>
<P>
Federal Treasurer Peter Costello, the third highest ranking
cabinet member, abstained, but Attorney-General Daryl Williams
said he would vote for change.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
