<HEADLINE> Dhaka Offers to Set Up Peacekeepers' Training Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has offered to set up
a training center for the United Nations' peacekeepers, a military
source said Friday.
</P>
<P>
This offer was made during a four-day conference here on South
Asian peacekeeping experience, which was organized by the
Bangladesh army with the United Nations' support to mark the 50th
anniversary of the U.N. peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to Dhaka's suitable location, Bangladesh Foreign
Minister Abdus Samad Azad told the conference, which ended on
Thursday, that over the past decade, Bangladesh had gained
considerable experience in peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is an ideal place for such a regional center, he
said, referring to Dhaka's commitment to upholding the U.N.
charter and protect world peace.
</P>
<P>
Peacekeeping had to be seen in the global context as part of
the quest for enduring peace, security and development, the
foreign minister added.
</P>
<P>
The conference were attended by military delegates from Canada,
China, India, Indonesia, Japan, Nepal, Pakistan, the Philippines,
Russia, Laos, Singapore, Sri Lanka, Britain the United States and
Bangladesh, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
The participants presented six papers, and discussed different
aspects of peacekeeping and came up with specific recommendations
during the conference, the source added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
