<HEADLINE> Survey: Urban Chinese Are Most Confident In Political Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Urban Chinese express the
strongest confidence in the country's political stability for
1998, according to survey results published today by the "China
Youth Daily."
</P>
<P>
The survey, "Reform situation and Social State of Mind," shows
that 79 percent of urban Chinese are confident the Chinese
government will maintain political stability in 1998. The survey
results also indicate that urban Chinese have bright expectations
for the country's development in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the level of confidence decreases in
the following order: 78 percent in social development; 74.4
percent in economic development; 71.3 percent in the government's
efforts to hold down prices; 63.3 percent in maintaining public
security; and 51.2 percent in the anti-corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted in November by the social survey
department under the State Commission for Restructuring the
Economy, covered 2,430 urban residents in 53 cities across the
country, and 91.2 percent of the returned questionnaires were
considered valid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
