<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Coffee to Hit New-Low due to El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's coffee production is
to fall to its lowest level in more than a decade due to heavy
rains since October and subsequent drought blamed on the El Nino
weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Coffee field would fall below 60,000 tons against an earlier
forecast of 65,000 tons, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Coffee traders said they expected no more than 42,000 tons
from the main crop and 18,000 tons from the "fly" mid crop for a
total of 60,000 tons. One trader even said it was possible
production would end up slightly above 51,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"You note that the figure of 65,000 tons was from the
ministry, not the (Kenya Coffee) board, which acknowledges a
production decline to 60,000 tons or below," one senior trader
said.
</P>
<P>
"If predicted drought is as intensive as they say it might be,
then we are looking at a drop of 25 percent from last year, which
would put Kenya's production at a figure around or just above
51,000 tons," added the trader with close links to the board.
</P>
<P>
Coffee ranks behind tea and tourism as Kenya's leading foreign
exchange earner. Heavy rains have already reduced production of
tea, sugar, maize, flowers, vegetables and sisal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
