<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Transport Up in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- China's trains averaged 2.49
million passengers per day in January, a rise of 7.6 percent over
1997.
</P>
<P>
Of that total, 663,000 were long-distance travelers (1,000
kilometers or farther), up 22.9 percent over 1997, according to
the latest statistics from the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
More people turned to highway or air travel for faster or more
comfortable service in recent years. The Ministry of Railways had
to adopt such measures as raising the speed limits on trains,
improving service and promoting sales to stop the decline of
railway transport.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the transport peak around Spring Festival when
large numbers of college students and non-local employees return
home for family reunions, the ministry added nearly 2,000
long-distance and 630 short-distance trains.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that from Jan. 8 to 31, railways transported
61.37 million passengers, up 4 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 69,200 carloads of cargo were also transported by
rail last month, including 31,000 carloads of coal. Transportation
of other key materials such as oil, metallurgical materials,
timber, grain, fertilizer and fresh food also exceeded targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
