<HEADLINE> Palestine not Satisfied With Current ME </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Executive Committee Chairman
of the Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) Abdul Rahman
said in Harare that Palestine was not satisfied by the current
stalemate over the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian special envoy made the statement after
meeting with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe Thursday to
deliver a message from Palestinian leader Yassar Arafat on the
stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Rahman, who is also in charge of refugees and displaced
Palestinians, said he was in Zimbabwe to solicit support from
Mugabe on the peace process and to appraise him, just as many of
his colleagues were appraising other world leaders, on the
deadlock in negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe is also current chairman of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Rahman said, "we want to draw the attention of the world to
how dangerous and grave the situation currently is in Palestine."
</P>
<P>
"All that we, as Palestinians, are calling for is for Israel
to implement the peace agreements signed by the previous
governments and recognize international treaties on the peace
process," said Rahman.
</P>
<P>
He said the political climate in Palestine was volatile and
could explode any time if sparked by even small incidents.
</P>
<P>
He also consulted Mugabe on what African governments could do
to lobby for a resumption of peaceful negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He said that as nobody in the world could guarantee peace in
the Middle East, the Palestinians would continue to struggle for
a negotiated settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
