<HEADLINE> Zambia's Currency Likely to Devaluate Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The high demand for foreign
exchange since the end of 1997 might cause a further depreciation
of Zambia's currency, Kwacha, the Citibank has predicated.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Friday quoted the Citibank treasury letter as
projecting a Kwacha depreciation between four and six percent and
a rate of between 1575 Kwacha and 1595 Kwacha per U.S. Dollars by
the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
"Indications are that tightness in the supply will continue
into February and we therefore project further depreciation of
the Kwacha," the publication said.
</P>
<P>
During last month, the Kwacha went down by about six percent
closing at 1500 Kwacha to a dollar and had it not been for Bank
of Zambia (BOZ) intervention through an injection of 23.6 million
dollars, the currency would have been weaker than it is.
</P>
<P>
According to BOZ, the central bank of the country, about 300
million dollars came in as foreign exchange inflows in 1997 from
various sources.
</P>
<P>
Against this, outlows amounted to 278 million dollars, leaving
a surplus of 22 million dollars which added to the reserves.
</P>
<P>
Of the total inflows, 54 percent went into debt servicing
highlighting the serious impact of the debt burden on the
country's foreign currency resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
