<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Boost Spending on Education, Welfare, Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government is set to enlarge its
expenditure by a big margin on education, health, social welfare
and housing in the financial year of 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
K. C. Kwong, Secretary for the Treasury Thursday announced the
government's draft estimates of expenditure for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
"The detailed draft estimates provide the funds needed to
implement all the improvements to services and investments in our
infrastructure announced by the Chief Executive in his Policy
Address last October," the official told a press conference here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government expenditure for the new financial year will
total at 233 billion HK dollars (30 billion US dollars), including
171.7 billion HK dollars (22 billion US dollars) on the recurrent
account and 61.3 billion HK dollars (8 billion US dollars) for
capital projects.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said that education, health, social welfare and housing
as a whole would account for 55.3 percent of the total public
expenditure in the 1998-99 financial year.
</P>
<P>
Education is expected to consume 43 billion HK dollars (5.5
billion US dollars), up 6.3 percent in real term from the previous
financial year. The SAR government plans to use the extra
resources to improve Hong Kong's basic education programs, such as
promoting the use of information technology in schools and
training teachers.
</P>
<P>
Health will cut a slice of 29 billion HK dollars (3.7 billion
US dollars), an increase of 5.4 percent in real term, while
recurrent expenditure on social welfare will jump by 13.6 percent
to 24.9 billion HK dollars (3.2 billion US dollars) in the next
financial year.
</P>
<P>
"Many of the improvements in health and social welfare will be
focused on meeting the needs of the elderly," said the SAR
government official.
</P>
<P>
There is also a substantial increase in the capital expenditure
in housing, a policy area to which the SAR's Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa has given priority since he took the post. Kwong said:
"Spending by the Housing Authority alone on construction projects
will increase by 40 percent in real term to 22.3 billion HK
dollars (2.8 billion US dollars). The total public expenditure in
housing will nearly double in 1998-99."
</P>
<P>
The Secretary for Treasury added that in the new financial
year, the government would also inject 14.5 billion HK dollars
(1.8 billion US dollars) into the West Rail project, a major
infrastructure program to be completed in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Kwong stressed that the expenditure draft was made in line with
the established prudent financial management principle of ensuring
that government expenditure, over time, grows no faster than the
forecast trend growth rate of the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
