<HEADLINE> 10 Air Crash Victims Identified in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Forensic experts have so far
identified only 10 victims who perished in the crash of Cebu
Pacific Air Flight 387 in the southern Philippines 12 days ago.
</P>
<P>
This was released Friday by Jesus Dureza, head of the
Presidential Action Center which coordinates the search and
retrieval operations of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Dureza said the bodies of the victims were already claimed one
after the other by their relatives as of Thursday. The process of
identification is still undergoing.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier that identifying the victims' body
parts retrieved from the crash site might take up to six months.
Victims relatives complained that the job is being done at a very
slow speed.
</P>
<P>
Dureza said the Presidential Action Center has set up a desk to
accept complaints filed by the relatives in relation to the
retrieval and identification of the victims.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated aircraft was carrying 99 passengers and five crew
members when it crashed in a mountain area in Misamis Oriental en
route from Manila to Cagayan de Oro city in the south. All people
aboard were believed dead.
</P>
<P>
The black box, or the Flight Data Recorder, of the plane has
been found and sent to Canada for experts there to determine the
cause of the air disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
