<HEADLINE> New Zealand Favors Peaceful Solution to Iraq Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley indicated on Friday that her country favors a
peaceful solution to the issue concerning United Nations weapon
inspectors in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone discussion with U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday morning, Shipley emphasized to Clinton New Zealand's
position that every diplomatic effort should be made, including
through the UN, to achieve a peaceful outcome, according to a
press statement from the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
She also told Clinton of New Zealand's deep concerns over
Iraq's retention of chemical and biological weapons and its
position that the UN weapons inspectors must be able to carry out
and complete the mandate given them by the UN Security Council in
1991.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Clinton underlined his commitment to, and
support for efforts underway to resolve the matter by diplomatic
means if at all possible, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said the cabinet will on Monday consider the question
of New Zealand participation in the multinational coalition being
formed to support and take military action to enforce the 1991
Security Council resolutions concerning Iraq.  
</P>
</TEXT>
