<HEADLINE> Equipment For Beijing's New Subway Being Given Duty-Free Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- China's General Administration
of Customs and the Beijing Customs Office recently decided to
waive more than 200 million yuan (24 million US dollars) in import
duties on equipment to be used for Beijing's new subway.
</P>
<P>
The equipment includes subway cars, escalators, and signal
equipment being used on the new line under Chang'an Avenue.
</P>
<P>
Work on the 13.5-km line, which runs from Fuxingmen on the west
to Bawangfen on the east, began in 1989. It was originally planned
for completion in 1996, but because of capital shortfalls, only
half of work has been completed.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the project was designated as a part of 50th
anniversary celebrations of the founding of the People's Republic
of China, in 1999. Builders have said they will finish the
project in September of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Bank, China Construction Bank, and the
Beijing municipal government have raised more than seven billion
yuan (843 million US dollars) to cover the money shortage.
</P>
<P>
Because the line runs under Beijing's political, cultural, and
business centers, it is expected to become the busiest line in
Beijing, carrying an estimated 420 million persons a year by
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Concern over Frequent River Flow Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Experts met recently in
Zhengzhou, capital of central China's Henan Province, to find out
ways to resolve the increasingly frequent stoppage of the Yellow
River, the second longest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Frequent droughts and excessive use of water by industries and
farming have greatly reduced the water volume of the giant river.
</P>
<P>
Since the first flow stoppage happened in 1972, the frequency
of stoppage has been on the rise. Last year, the river in the
lower reaches dried up 13 times with a total break of 266 days.
</P>
<P>
The rampant sabotages have brought in heavy economic losses to
the provinces in the lower reaches. In 1997, the stoppage caused
long-lasting droughts for 1.3 million ha. of farmlands in Henan
and Shandong provinces. Shandong alone suffered losses worth about
13.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River Water Conservancy Committee have submitted to
higher authorities proposals on the management of the Yellow River
water volume and the timely control on the water volume of the
Yellow River for official approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
