<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Gas Dealers Protest Against VAT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Cars, motorbikes and other
vehicles lined up on Friday for fuels as an indefinite strike
involving gas dealers has been called in Nepal to protest against
the value added tax (VAT), which is to become fully operational
the same day in the country.
</P>
<P>
Long queues were seen in the morning before the gas stations in
the capital as the Nepal Petroleum Dealers Association (NPDA) has
made the call for an indefinite strike from Friday. Some gas
stations are just shut up.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the gas dealers have protested against
the VAT. On November 17, 1997, one day after the VAT was
introduced formally in the country, they refused to buy petroleum
products from the state-run oil corporation, causing an upsurge of
demand and ensuing long queues.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said the NPDA has demanded waiver of the VAT on
the petroleum products excluding lubricant, but the government
refused.
</P>
<P>
NPDA officials said they were ready to withdraw the strike call
if the government exempts petroleum dealers from billing their
sales.
</P>
<P>
As negotiations between the business community and the
government came to a deadlock, the Federation of Nepalese Chamber
of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI) has called for a closing of
business in the country from 10 a.m. to 12 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although the VAT was introduced last year, it was not enforced
at all places and for all sectors for a grace period of three
months.
</P>
<P>
However, the row between the government and the business
community has intensified during this period, which has severely
affected the VAT registration.
</P>
<P>
In a public notification, the FNCCI said it would not negotiate
with the government over the VAT unless octroi is abolished.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sharma has promised to abolish octroi once the
VAT is fully operational.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
