<HEADLINE> American Ice Hockey Player Sent Home Due to Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Ice hockey player Shawn
McEachern of the United States has been sent home due to lower back
strain, Team USA general manager Lou Lamoriello announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jamie Langenbrunner will fill the vacant place in the team which
will play Sweden in its opening game at the ice hockey Dream
Tournament at the Olympic Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
However, Langenbrunner will not arrive in Nagano in time for the
opening match on Friday or for Saturday's game against Belarus.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the injury to Shawn's lower back has not progressed
to the point that our medical personnel felt he could be cleared to
play," Lamoriello said. "We are fortunate, however, to have a player
with the skill and ability that Jamie Langenbrunner brings to our
team. Jamie has had an outstanding season thus far for the Dallas
Stars, and we are proud to welcome him to the U.S. team."
</P>
<P>
In only his second full season with the Stars and fourth overall in
professional ice hockey, Langenbrunner ranks fourth on the team in
scoring with 42 points in 56 games. He is third on the team in
power-play goals with six and fourth in game-winning goals with four.
</P>
<P>
Langenbrunner was honoured as the Star' Rookie of the Year last
season after registering 39 points in 76 regular-season games. He
finished the season ranked fourth in assists, sixth in scoring and
tied for ninth in goals among all rookies in the National Hockey
League.
</P>
<P>
Langenbruner began his professional playing career in 1994-95,
appearing in two regular-season games for the Stars and 11 playoff
contests for the International Hockey League's Kalamazoo K-Wings. He
split time between Dallas and the IHL's Michigan K-Wings in 1995-96
before playing his first full season with the stars in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Langenbrunner's previous international playing experience includes
competing for two United States National Junior Teams (1994 and 1995)
at the World Junior Championships. 
</P>
