<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Urged to Ratify Nuclear Test-ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
Thursday urged the Senate to approve a global nuclear test ban
treaty in 1998, saying it would put a brake on the arms race and
deter other nations from developing such weapons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the National Press Club in Washington,
U.S. Secretary Federico Pena said the treaty would improve his
country's ability to "detect and deter nuclear explosive testing"
by other nations.
</P>
<P>
"The best way to ensure that other countries do not test," he
said, "is for us to lead by example and ratify the accord, thereby
encouraging other countries to do so."
</P>
<P>
The Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which was concluded in late
1996, has been signed by 148 countries so far, but only eight
countries have ratified it.
</P>
<P>
Pena said a special conference of the nations that have
ratified the treaty would be held late next year to encourage more
nations to sign, and the U.S. risked being excluded if the Senate
does not ratify the accord.
</P>
<P>
The treaty needs to be approved by a two-thirds majority of the
Republican-controlled Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
