<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Officials Appeal for Support for IMF Package Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
Thursday joined hands to appeal for backing of an 18 billion U.S.
dollar funding package for the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The two men told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
approval of the funds would send a badly needed signal to the
world that the United States was prepared to do its part to ensure
the stability of the global financial system.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan pointed out that it was critical in the current Asian
crisis to support efforts of the IMF to "restore trust in the
system."
</P>
<P>
The IMF has already committed 100 billion dollars in emergency
loans for South Korea, Indonesia and Thailand for stabilizing
their economies that have been hit hard since last summer by
plunging currencies and stock prices.
</P>
<P>
The 18 billion dollars being sought from Congress approval
would not be used for those rescues but would replenish IMF
reserves so that the IMF could handle future crises.
</P>
<P>
"If the crisis was to spread more broadly to emerging markets
throughout the globe, which we are all working hard to avoid, then
American workers and businesses could be far more severely
affected," Rubin stressed.
</P>
<P>
Rubin and Greenspan also expressed similar view that poor
economic policies were the cause of the currency and market
meltdowns in Asia. The only way to restore investor confidence was
for the countries to follow the IMF reform programs, they argued.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the Senate committee endorsed the view that the
IMF should be supported to take the lead in the Asian crisis,
based on the success of a 50 billion dollar bailout for Mexico's
economy in earlier 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the committee chairman, Senator Jesse Helms expressed that
he wanted reforms to ensure greater openness in the 182-nation
institution, including allowing the General Accounting Office,
Congress' investigating arm, to review IMF books.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the biggest obstacle to
congressional approval of the new IMF package appeared to be not
in the Senate, but the House, where anti-abortion forces are
vowing to defeat the proposal unless the administration
compromises on an unrelated abortion issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
