<HEADLINE> Most Applicants in S.Lankan Pass Written Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Out of about 104,000 people
applying for driving licenses and who underwent written tests in
Sri Lanka last year, some 100,000 have obtained required marks,
Commissioner of Motor Traffic D.S. Edirisinghe said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The written test was introduced by the Department of Motor
Traffic on January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Those who undergo the test must obtain a minimum of 75 marks to
be eligible to have their driving tests.
</P>
<P>
Edirisinghe said after the introduction of the written test,
many applicants came with a good knowledge of the highway code of
Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
To get fully prepared for the test, many applicants spent a
certain amount of time reading the Highway Code Book, issued by
the department. A total of 50,000 copies were sold last year.
</P>
<P>
The test is a major step the department has taken to improve
highway safety. It is also used to ensure every driving license is
issued to the right person who is qualified.
</P>
<P>
Each applicant must submit his birth certificate and national
identity card before he or she is allowed to participate in the
written test and those who fail will not be allowed to proceed for
driving test on road. 
</P>
</TEXT>
