<HEADLINE> South Korean Trade Unions Cancel Plan of General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Korean Confederation of
Trade Unions (KCTU), the second largest labor union of the
country, has decided to cancel a general strike scheduled for
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by KCTU Emergency Committee late Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
"We made the decision in consideration of public opinions
expressing concerns over the repeat of the national economic
crisis," Dan Byung-ho of the committee said earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, the cancellation doesn't mean an approval for
large-scale dismissals, Dan said, adding that KCTU will spare no
time to prevent the National Assembly from passing a bill of
legalizing mass layoffs at the ongoing special session and ask for
the step-down of conglomerate heads and donation of their private
assests to the laid-off.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from labor, capital and government last week
signed an accord to legalize mass layoffs. Analysts predicted that
at least one million South Koreans will lose their job this year.
</P>
<P>
But, KCTU, which formed a new leadership after ousting leaders
responsible for signing the agreement, Monday threatened to stage
a general strike to boycott the accord, under which, capital could
dismiss workers when businesses face "emergency situation" such as
financial troubles, merger and acquisition.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government announced on Wednesday that it
would deal hard with "illegal" labor acts.
</P>
<P>
Amid a possible strike since Monday, the Seoul stock market has
showed a downward trend and plunged more than 20 points to below
500 points Thursday morning while the won depreciated to 1,620 won
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF), which agreed last
December to grant 57 billion U.S. dollars in loans to South Korea
to help bail out the country from the financial crisis, has warned
of a possible reoccurrence of the foreign currency crisis if the
nation's labor unions walk out.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed with the IMF for the bailout loans,
South Korea has to open its markets, shut down its ailing
financial institutions and legalize mass layoffs in the course of
economic restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Produce Cleaner Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Stated will
produce cars that will reduce 70 percent of smog-causing emission,
under a program formally launched by Clinton administration on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of emission "will be the equivalent of taking
10.5 million cars off the road by 2001, protecting the health of
millions of Americans," Vice President Al Gore told officials from
the Big Three domestic automakers, Ford, Chrysler and General
Motors, and 10 foreign automakers at a White House ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The cars will be sold this fall in eight eastern states and the
District of Columbia as 1999 models and will be sold nationwide
beginning with 2001 models.
</P>
<P>
The Environmental Protection Agency estimates the new models of
cars will produce 70 percent less smog-causing hydrocarbons and 50
percent less nitrogen oxides.
</P>
<P>
Car emissions are a large portion of smog in the country. In
some states, vehicles cause about 30 to 43 percent of the ozone
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The 10 foreign automakers who have agreed to the plan are
Honda, Toyota, Nissan, BMW, Mercedes, Saab, Subaru, Suzuki, Volvo
and Rolls Royce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
