<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Denies Possibility of Pegging Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 13 (Xinhua) -- A Thai central bank official
has firmly denied market speculation that the bank would establish
a currency board and fix exchange rates for the baht.
</P>
<P>
Duangmanee Vongpradhip, director of the bank governor's office,
said Thursday that policy makers had never considered changing the
float system of the baht which was introduced on July 2 last year.
</P>
<P>
She also denied reports that the central bank had discussed the
currency board issue with officials of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the IMF director for Asia-Pacific, Hubert Neiss,
also denied any discussion about a currency board with Thailand.
</P>
<P>
As for Indonesia's plan to establish a currency board, the
central bank official said it "did not affect Thailand at all."
</P>
<P>
Speculation that Thailand was considering a currency board
contributed to the sharp rise of baht in the offshore market
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The baht jumped to as high as 41.5 to the dollar, closing at
43.1. However, it lost ground Thursday, closing at 45.35 after
opening at 43.8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
