<HEADLINE> Four Polar Researchers Rescued Near Bulgarian Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Four researchers trapped on a
floe near the island of Livingston in Antarctica have been rescued
by a Uruguayan helicopter, the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four researchers, members of a team of Bulgarian geologists
and accompanied by Moon Jang Cho of South Korea and Andreas Wait
of Germany, were trapped during a snowstorm on a floe that chipped
off a glacier on the Perounika Plateau, two kilometers from the
Bulgarian polar base.
</P>
<P>
The four polar researchers were reportedly on an expedition to
Mount Murev, which is located 20 kilometers from their base, to
study a dead volcano and residue rocks.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a team of glaciologists had descended into a
30-meter crack in the Perounika Glacier to study the effect of
global warming.
</P>
<P>
All members of the Bulgarian expedition were reportedly in good
health and anxious to continue their research, which is scheduled
to end in late February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
