<HEADLINE> French Skiier Wins Men's Downhill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Jean-Luc Cretier of France
claimed the title of the men's downhill race which witnessed crash of
the pre-race favourite Hermann Maier of Austria at the 18th Olympic
Winter Games in Habuba on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cretier, starting at the third, sprinted to win the race at one
minutes and 50.11 seconds. Lasse Kjus of Norway was second with 4.54
seconds behind and Hames Trinkl of Austria third at 1:50.63.
</P>
<P>
After finishing his run, Cretuer watched the crash of Maier, who
started at the fourth place.
</P>
<P>
Maier, former bricklayer, crashed after midway from the starting
gate and somersaulted twice and landed on his back after breaking the
safety net. Fortunately, he was unhurt.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian managed to stand up and walked without help.
</P>
<P>
The race was delayed by about nine minutes to repair the net. Some
other skiiers also lost their balance at the same turn but did not
crash.
</P>
<P>
Italian Luca Cattaneo was also crashed and airlifted by a
helicopter to a nearby hospital.
</P>
<P>
The downhill race, which has been delayed three times at the
Olympics, saw 15 skiiers out of competitions.
</P>
<P>
For Cretier, it was a memmorable moment to win the gold, which
should had been decided on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I skied really well, I have fast skis and I think that is what did
it," said Cretier, who would retire after the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't know if I could win before today. The course was good on
the top and one the bottom although there were some problems in
between.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people did a lot of work on the course and I was
satisfied with it. I think it is because of my long experience in
racing that helped me today."
</P>
<P>
"I can't believe it at the moment although I am sure I will later,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
