<HEADLINE> HIV Discoverer: "Triple-drug" Therapy Efficiency Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- French researcher Luc
Montagnier who discovered in 1983 the human immune-deficiency
virus (HIV) said here Thursday that the efficiency of the
so-called "Triple-drug" therapy is not verified yet.
</P>
<P>
The efficiency of the Triple-drug, which it's said halts HIV
from replicating in an infected person, is long debated.
</P>
<P>
Montagnier said that the virus keeps itself latent in some
places and a way to restore human immunological system has not
been found.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the AIDS outlook in the world here, the scientist
said that some 16,000 persons are infected with the HIV every day
and the number of the infected has reached 35 million.
</P>
<P>
However, Montagnier said, with no cure for AIDS found yet,
investigation, prevention and treatment are the only way to combat
the disease.
</P>
<P>
The French scientist also proposed establishing a regional
center in Uruguay for AIDS investigation, which needs an initial
outlay of half a million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Invited by the Spanish Association of Uruguay, the scientist
has met with Uruguayan President Julio Maria Sanguinetti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Agrees to Relax Aid Condition for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) agreed to relax a key condition of Thailand's economic
bailout which requires the country to post a budget surplus in
fiscal 1998, IMF Asia-Pacific Director Hubert Neiss said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will be now allowed to have a budget deficit of 1-2
percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in the fiscal year ending
on September 30, Neiss said.
</P>
<P>
According to the IMF's previous criterion, Thailand must
achieve a budget surplus equivalent to 1 percent of GDP, or about
69 billion baht (1.5 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The IMF will also allow Thailand to ease its high domestic
interest rates in a bid to guard against speculative attacks on
the beleaguered baht "sometime after the currency market
stabilizes," Neiss said.
</P>
<P>
Neiss explained that an improvement in Thailand's economic
outlook had prompted the IMF to allow an easing of the conditions
of its 17.2 billion dollar bailout package.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Thai economy had slowed down to such an
extent since the IMF program began that a continued stringent
austerity regime may trigger a new economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Neiss said he was "satisfied" with the revised conditions which
will restore confidence to the country's battered financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
He also gave a thumbs up to the new government's efforts to
avert economic meltdown, saying the economy "would not return to
the same state as it was, as the government has control of the
financial system and is creating stability."
</P>
<P>
The IMF's move came amid the publication of the world monetary
body's second quarterly review of Thailand's progress in applying
its rescue package.
</P>
<P>
The IMF is expected to allow the unblocking of the third
segment of the 17.2 billion dollar package extended to Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0258 </DOCNO>
