<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern Chinese City Finds New Way to Use Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, February 13 (Xinhua) -- A new system of employment for
police in Chengdu, the capital of China's Sichuan Province, has
broken the "iron rice bowl" so that police who are unqualified can
lose their jobs at any time.
</P>
<P>
Since the new system was implemented two years ago, some 963
policemen have been appointed to positions at various levels in
the city's public security bureau, and 117 who were found to be
unqualified have been dismissed from office.
</P>
<P>
The average age of the police officials has dropped three years
and all the new police officials have at least two year's of
college education.
</P>
<P>
Local policemen are also becoming more dedicated in their work,
and the number of cases solved by the city's public security
offices in 1997 increased 37 percent from the previous
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Equity Investments Surge in Philippines in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Despite the debilitating
effects of the currency crisis, corporate investments by
newly-established firms rose by 41 percent to 59.7 billion pesos
(1.5 billion U.S. dollars) in the Philippines last year, local
press reports said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said data from the Securities and Exchange
Commission (SEC) showed that new investments in foreign and local
companies did not dwindle during the third quarter right after the
onset of the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Fresh equity infusion from established companies also increased
for most part of the year. During the second half, investments in
existing companies grew by an average 14 percent, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
The figures led the SEC to conclude that the Asian currency
crisis failed to dampen foreign direct investors' interest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good indication that confidence of the international
community in the Philippine fundamentals still remains," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists did not agree, arguing that foreign
direct investments in the country dropped by some 40 percent last
year due to the currency crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
