<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Singapore Jointly Produce Carbon Dioxide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Singapore have
begun to jointly produce liquid and solid carbon dioxide in
Myanmar's Thanlyin refinery in the south of the capital Yangon for
domestic industrial use.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Carbonix joint venture factory, established between
the state-run Myanmar Petrochemical Enterprise (MPE) and the Nur
Investment and Trading Pte. Ltd. of Singapore, went into
production Thursday, the New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The factory, using carbon dioxide wastes from industries,
produces 24 tons of liquefied carbon dioxide and six tons of
solidified gas (dry ice) per day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a new acetylene factory in Yangon, jointly built by
Myanmar and China, has been producing 200 cylinders of liquefied
gas per day since it began operation last September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
