<HEADLINE> Denmark, China to Enhance Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COPENHAGEN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and Danish Foreign Minister Niels H.
Petersen agreed here Thursday that their two countries will
enhance bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During talks here, Li said Denmark was one of the Western
countries that established diplomatic relations with the People's
Republic of China soon after its birth.
</P>
<P>
China and Denmark have enjoyed a long history of cooperation,
he said, leaders of the two countries have also maintained
exchanges and contacts which have enhanced mutual understanding
and greatly promoted cooperation in all fields.
</P>
<P>
Li said there is no fundamental conflict of interest between
China and Denmark. The Chinese government is willing to join
hands with the Danish government to establish long-term and stable
relations of friendly cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Petersen said the Danish
government attaches great importance to Danish-Chinese relations.
The Danish government hopes the two countries can strengthen
cooperation in the fields of culture, science, agriculture, food
processing, energy, and environment.
</P>
<P>
He said the exchange of visits between leaders of the two
countries will help promote friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
He said Danmark supports China's efforts to join the World
Trade Organization at an early date, and it also observes the "one
China policy." In addition, the Danish government has been
encouraging more enterprises to invest in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said the two-way trade between the two nations has been
steadily increasing and that economic and technological
cooperation has been improved. China has also adopted new
preferential policies to attract foreign investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said he is confident that future economic relations between
China and Denmark will be bright.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged views on the south-east Asian financial
crisis. Peterson said he believed the Asian economy will continue
to be energetic and competitive in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
