<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Say They Are Satisfied with The Country's Opening-Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- A recent study of 5,138 urban
residents in China found that more people are satisfied with the
country's opening-up.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was done by the Horizon Market Survey and
Analysis Company, showed that 34.6 percent of those questioned say
the opening-up is good and should continue, an increase of 14
percentage points from 1995, and that 24.9 percent believe the
opening-up hasn't gone far enough, and 11 percent think it's gone
too far, while 21.1 percent think it's not balanced.
</P>
<P>
The increasing satisfaction with the opening-up is a result of
the further opening in the central and western parts of the
country, and to the better use of foreign funds, the researchers
conclude.
</P>
<P>
The greatest worries, they say, are unhealthy tendencies like
drug addiction and Aids coming from foreign countries, the
infiltration of foreign culture, and the brain drain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
