<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Reiterates Opposition to Military Action Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev Thursday reiterated his country's opposition to military
strikes against Iraq, and categorically denied that Russia had
negotiated the sale of equipment to Iraq to make proscribed
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference with U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen, Sergeyev stressed that Iraq must comply with
U.N. resolutions, but compliance should be achieved only through
diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
He said if the U.S. turned to force to settle the Iraqi
crisis, it would hurt and set back bilateral ties between Russia
and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to relate to you our deep concern over the
possible prospects of Russian-U.S. relations in the military
field, especially if military actions are taken," Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also denied a report in The Washington Post on
Thursday that U.N. weapons inspectors had found documents prepared
by Iraqi officials on Russian-Iraqi negotiations. The negotiations
reportedly would have led to a multimillion dollar deal for Russia
to sell equipment to Iraq to make biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Cohen acknowledged that Russia and the U.S. are divergent over
how to settle the Iraqi problem, but added, "the strength of the
underlying relationship is paramount. Where we have differences,
we will work out our differences."
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirm U.S. resolve to use force against Iraq, but
ruled out the possibility of using nuclear weapons against the
Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived here Wednesday on a two-day visit. It is his
first visit to Russia as Pentagon chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
