<HEADLINE> EU Promises to Help Deal With Thai Social Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has pledged
to help solve Thailand's social problems through collaboration
with non-governmental organizations, according to Thai Foreign
Minister Surin Pitsuwan.
</P>
<P>
The EU is trying to play a more active role in helping Thailand
solve its economic problems including social side-effects, Surin
was quoted as saying by the local press Friday.
</P>
<P>
The EU was considering such financial facilities as the
European Investment Bank and the Bank for Development and
Reconstruction to help support Thailand's social programs with
collaboration between European and Thai NGOs, but the amount and
modalities had not yet been worked out, Surin said after meeting
with EU representatives Thursday led by British Ambassador James
Hodge, whose country currently holds the EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Surin also asked the EU to revise the
dumping allegations of Thai agricultural and industrial products.
The EU has imposed anti-dumping duties on 13 items of Thai
exports.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed how to move forward cooperation in
the Asia-Europe meeting, to be held for the second time in April
in London.  
</P>
</TEXT>
