<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decision to Send Troops to Gulf Questioned in Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A group of Democratic Left
Alliance deputies in the Polish Parliament are challenging the
government's legal right to send troops to the Persian Gulf to
participate in a possible U.S.-led military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In an official statement issued on Wednesday, the Polish
government said it is prepared to send appropriate supportive
troops to the gulf if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the statement, the deputies said that what is in
question is not the pretext used by the government to make the
decision, but the way to make it, the Forum daily reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Poland is neither a signatory to any international treaty or
law that could justify the deployment of its forces outside its
territory under the country's constitution, nor is it an official
member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), they said.
</P>
<P>
Even if Poland were an official NATO member, the decision to
send troops to the gulf could remain questionable because the
U.S.-proposed military strike against Iraq is not a joint action
of the treaty organization, they added.
</P>
<P>
As to Poland's participation in the 1991 gulf war, the deputies
said the decision was legitimate because Poland did so in
compliance with resolutions adopted by the United Nations at that
time.
</P>
<P>
In the current case, however, with three of its permanent
members, namely Russia, China and France, categorically opposing
the use of force, the U.N. Security Council did not authorize any
member to launch a military strike against Iraq, they said.
</P>
<P>
The deputies also accused the government of making the decision
to send troops without consulting the president and other state
offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0282 </DOCNO>
