<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- This year cotton undershirts output will reach 932
million units, a 7.1 percent increase over the 870 million pieces
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to research of the Brazilian Institute of Studies and
Industrial Market, the production and sale of cotton undershirts
in the Brazilian market has increased in the last years, since the
figure was 862 million pieces in 1995, and 837 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican inflation dropped last January to 1.59
percent, against 2.06 percent registered in the same month of
1997, according to Economy Ministry statistics.
</P>
<P>
Economy Minister Jose Leon Desanti attributed this drop in the
consumer prices index to the economy of this country reactivation
and growth.
</P>
<P>
Desanti also announced that the aim of the government is to end
the year with an 11 percent inflation, very close to the 11.20
percent registered in 1997.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Commerce and Industrial Promotion Ministry
(Secofi) of Mexico announced the application of provisional
compensatory quotas of between 10.55 percent and 24.12 percent to
the import of cut bond paper from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Secofi explained that the measure was taken to prevent more
damage to the national industry that produces this input, as long
as the anti-dumping investigation continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
