<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Major U.S.-led Attacks on Iraq Since Gulf War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Following is a chronology of
major U.S.-led attacks on Iraq since the end of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
December 1992 -- U.S. F-16 fighter shoots down an Iraqi MiG in
the West-imposed no-fly zone in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
January 7, 1993 -- About 110 U.S. and allied aircraft strike Iraqi
missile sites in the no-fly zone in retaliation for what they
consider as violations of Gulf War ceasefire terms. Baghdad says
19 killed in attack.
</P>
<P>
June 27, 1993 -- U.S. warships fire 23 cruise missiles at
Baghdad, destroying Iraqi intelligence service headquarters
wing. Missiles kill six people. The attack was ordered to revenge
alleged Iraqi plot to kill former U.S. president George Bush.
</P>
<P>
July and August 1993 -- U.S. planes strike anti-aircraft
missile sites in series of missile attacks in no-fly zone over
southern and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
September 3-4, 1996 -- U.S. forces fire 27 Tomahawk missiles at
targets in southern Iraq. The targets include radar stations,
ground-to-air missile batteries and anti-aircraft command centers.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi army says five soldiers died and 19 people, including
civilians, were injured.
</P>
<P>
September 4, 1996 -- The U.S. launches a second assault on
Iraqi air defenses in the south, firing 17 cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi army says one person was killed and seven wounded in
the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
