<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, February 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG -- Chinese Premier Li Peng arrived Thursday
afternoon in Luxembourg, the first leg of his week-long
three-nation European tour.
</P>
<P>
Li was on a two-day official good-will visit at the invitation
of Luxembourg Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker, who gave the
Chinese guest a red-carpet welcome at the airport.
</P>
<P>
In his host's company, the Chinese premier reviewed the guards
of honor of Luxembourg armed forces.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech upon arrival -- the first time by a Chinese
premier since the two countries forged diplomatic ties in 1972, Li
said he was "very pleased" to visit this West European
country. (Luxembourg-China-Li Peng's Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WARSAW -- Five Polish aid workers held hostage by Chechen
kidnappers two months ago flew home Thursday morning, a report of
the Polish Press Agency said.
</P>
<P>
When meeting the five workers, Polish Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek said his government is always ready to help Poles abroad.
</P>
<P>
The five were abducted on December 17 while delivering
humanitarian aid materials to a village in the Northern Caucasus
republic. They were freed by Chechen security forces on
Monday. (Poland-Hostages)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov appointed several
Islamist opposition leaders to his coalition government, the
Interfax news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Rakhmonov's spokesman Zafar Saidov as saying
that Davlat Usmon, chief of staff of the opposition's armed
forces, was named minister of economy and foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Other opposition members appointed were Davlatbek Makhsudov as
minister of water resources and Khudoberdy Khuliknazarov as labor
and employment minister.
</P>
<P>
And Rakhmim Karimov was to head the Tajik Customs Committee.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was seen as a key step in the settlement of a
four-year civil war in the Central Asian
country. (Tajikistan-Cabinet-Appointment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Military experts Thursday predicted a
U.S.-British air strike on Iraq, once decided, might take place
around February 26 when a new moon just arrives.
</P>
<P>
They said the next new moon, on Feb. 26, creates a potential
window of opportunity for a possible U.S. air strike on Iraq as a
concealing dark sky, with little or no visible crescent, is the
best time to launch an attack.
</P>
<P>
"There are three or four nights of darkness on either side of
the new moon," said Geoff Chester, a spokesman for the U.S. Naval
Observatory. "It certainly helps to have no moon. When it's full,
it illuminates the sky." (US-Iraq-Showdown)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan Thursday formally
invited Iraq to send a delegation to the U.N. headquarters in New
York to hold discussions on the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal, the
Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Annan's invitation has been sent to Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said in his invitation that he has noticed the
Iraqi complaint about his proposal after he submitted it to the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Annan proposed earlier this month to increase the amount of oil
Iraq can sell under the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal to 5.2 billion
U.S. dollars over six months from original 2 billion dollars to
alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqi people. (Annan-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Prime Minister Romano Prodi of Italy Thursday
reaffirmed his country's demand to become a founding member of the
single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
"Italy has made all efforts to meet the fiscal criteria
required for joining the the European Monetary Union," said Prodi
in a speech at the opening ceremony of the new fairground of the
southern Germany city of Munich.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the sustainability of the fiscal discipline imposed
by his government, which has been doubted occasionally by some
other European Union countries, including Germany, Prodi said that
"a culture of fiscal stability" had been introduced in Italy,
which would have an irreversible effect on the state
budget. (Italy-Euro) 
</P>
</TEXT>
