<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's Shandong to Improve Real Estate Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, February 13 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
will intensify the housing reform as part of its efforts to uplift
its real estate market, sources from the Provincial Construction
Committee said today.
</P>
<P>
The province has recently put forward a plan of establishing an
open-market housing market catering to the demands of ordinary
families and a economic housing market which will provide flats to
families with low incomes.
</P>
<P>
It has also decided to provide all urban families in towns and
cities with flats with good facilities by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
To realize the goal, the province has started to practice new
housing reform measures including the establishment of a public
accumulative fund for housing, abolition of welfare housing
distribution, and adding housing subsidies in workers' salaries.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the reality that many open-market flats
remain idle and unsold, the province urged real estate developers
to sell some of the open-market flats at lower prices to families
with low and medium incomes.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the province has also adjusted taxes to bring
down prices of open-market flats and has vigorously expanded
financial business on housing such as offering mortgage loans to
individuals in a bid to support housing consumption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fishing Ban Protects Whitebait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Taihu Lake, one the country's
five largest inland lakes, will continue tightening its management
during the half-year moratorium on fishing this year to protect
whitebait.
</P>
<P>
From February 1 to August 31, fishing will be suspended in this
lake in east China's Jiangsu province, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Artificially fertilized roe will be put into the lake to help
restore the whitebait resource, a profitable species with great
value which have deteriorated in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Taihu Lake has introduced the fishing ban every year since
1984. But lured by high profits, over-fishing became more and more
serious, which made production plunge in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Pollution and drought were also reasons for the reduction in
whitebait.
</P>
<P>
Annual production of whitebait decreased to 540 tons in 1995
and to 500 tons in 1996, compared with 1,500 to 2,000 tons during
the 1985-94 period.
</P>
<P>
The production rebounded to more than 900 tons last year,
nearly double that of the previous year, thanks to the
strengthened efforts.
</P>
<P>
Other large inland lakes such as Chaohu Lake in Anhui province
also have such protective measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
