<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
major economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the
past few days.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Tax revenue in Argentina amounted last year to
48.5 billion pesos, almost seven percent increase over the 45.4
billion pesos of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The revenue for the value-added tax was 20.476 billion dollars,
42 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Income tax revenue was 8.334 billion pesos and employers taxes
7.234 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean imports of personal computers reached
142,502 units from January to November in 1997, a 13.4 percent
increase over the same period of 1996, the International Data
Corp. said.
</P>
<P>
Compaq increased its sales in the country during the period
almost 96 percent and got a 23.7 percent share of the market, five
points above its closest competitor, IBM. Acer came in third.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaraguan poultry producers demanded the government
to bar the import of eggs from El Salvador at dumping prices.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Poultry Producers of Nicaragua said
that Salvadoran firms send their surplus at prices under the
prices they sold in their own country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
