<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Island Development Zone Establishes Chemical Center (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, February 13 (Xinhua) -- A chemical production center is
under construction in the Yangpu Economic Development Zone in
China's southern island province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
The zone is on the northwest part of the island, about 140 km
from the provincial capital of Haikou. Offshore areas near the
zone are rich in natural gas. Some basins south of the island have
natural gas reserves estimated at 251 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
China's Central Government has given its support to the
center. In March of 1996, Premier Li Peng visited Yangpu and
encouraged Hainan's economic development through similar
industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
The China National Offshore Oil Corp. (CNOOC) announced last
March that it would put 15.5 billion yuan (1.87 billion US
dollars) into the country's largest modern chemical fertilizer
project at the Yangpu Zone.
</P>
<P>
The entire project will mean building six offshore oil
platforms, drilling 32 wells, and laying a 243-km gas pipeline to
Yangpu. It will also mean building two of China's largest
fertilizer plants, each with an annual production capacity of
450,000 tons of ammonia and 1.6 million tons of urea.
</P>
</TEXT>
