<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists: China's Grain Output to Reach Last Year's Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Leading economists here
forecast that China's grain output in 1998 will reach the level of
last year.
</P>
<P>
They drew the conclusion at a high-profile meeting held
recently by the prestigious Chinese Academy of Social Sciences,
attended by experts from both State Council departments and
research institutes, including the State Planning Commission and
the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
China's grain output in 1997 reached 490 billion kilograms, the
second biggest harvest in history.
</P>
<P>
Experts are optimistic about the overall grain production in
spite of the fact that summer grain has been affected by bad
weather early this year.
</P>
<P>
They held that China's grain production capability has
been remarkably improved, and a balanced market demand and supply
has been basically achieved.
</P>
<P>
In addition, sharp fluctuations of grain prices has become an
past tense term, thanks to the tightened macro-control imposed by
the government.
</P>
<P>
However, they warned the government and the related departments
to be aware of the possible decrease of grain output this year as
the existing production capability is not strong enough and the
supply and demand relationship is still weak.
</P>
<P>
They held that importance should be attached to the reform of
state-owned grain enterprises and the circulation system,
introducing market competition, developing grain warehouse and
better coordinate the country's internal and foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
