<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trying to Make Better Use of Water in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Noted scientist Chen Mengxiong
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences has concluded that more
efficient use of water resources can improve agricultural
production greatly in China, after comparing the use of water
resources in Beijing and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Chen explains that Beijing's amount of arable land is similar
to that of Israel, which has serious water-deficiency problems,
and it is one of the most efficient users of water resource in the
world. Beijing's use of fresh water for agriculture is 2.4 times
that of Israel, and its agricultural output is less than
Israel's. Total output value could be increased almost three
times, from the current 3.43 billion yuan (413 million US dollars)
to 9.57 billion yuan if Beijing's use of water resources for
agriculture were similar to Israel's.
</P>
<P>
Improved irrigation techniques and water use methods are better
means of increasing China's agricultural output than diverting
water from distant places, Chen says.
</P>
<P>
China's total amount of water resources is 2.6 trillion to 2.7
trillion cu.m., or seven percent of the world's total. Per capita
water resources is about 2,200 cu.m., or 30 percent of the world's
average.
</P>
<P>
In a country like this, which has to meet the food demand of 22
percent of the world's population, with 7 percent of the world's
water resources and arable land, increasing agricultural output by
improving water use is a way to kill two birds with one stone,
Chen concludes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Retail Price Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- Manufactured goods and farm
produce were cheaper but service items were more expensive in
Shanghai in 1997, resulting in a decrease in the city's retail
price index and marginal growth in its consumer price index.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index was 988 and the consumer price index
102.8 last year, the slowest growth since 1985, when the city
stopped controlling market prices, according to the city's
statistics bureau.
</P>
<P>
Food, cigarettes, soft drinks, alcohol, and clothing were
cheaper last year, but the price of water, electricity, fuel,
telephone calls, tuition, and rents was up.
</P>
<P>
The report estimates that market prices will slightly rebound
this year, with the consumer price index and retail price index
growing six and three percent respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
