<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt to Review Domestic Borrowing Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' fiscal
managers will review the government's borrowing program in a bid
to come up with a "more effective and responsible" debt management
method to help bring down interest rates, local press reports said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted newly installed Finance Secretary Salvador
Enriquez as saying that the review will determine if the current
process of borrowing every week through issuing Treasury bills
will have to be stopped.
</P>
<P>
Every Monday, the government auctions off five billion pesos
worth of Treasury bills that mature in 91 days, 182 days and 364
days, and sometimes in 42 days and 63 days.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said the government may have to adopt a policy to
borrow "only at the most advantageous time and not in the time of
need".
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that a more effective debt management would
be to borrow in bulk during times of lower interest rates as
opposed to the weekly flotation since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the current Treasury bill flotation system
will only continue resulting in high Treasury bill rates, and
therefore high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The high Treasury bill rates prevailing since last year,
particularly that of the benchmark 91-day maturity, have been
keeping interest rates of commercial banks at unreasonable levels
which are allegedly killing the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
However, Enriquez's plan drew a lukewarm reaction from traders
who said the scheme will only remove the effectivity of the T-bill
as a benchmark instrument and also will not necessarily translate
into lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, I know for a fact that the auction is not controlled
by the banks because even if the banks quote off-market from the
Bureau of Treasury projections, the bureau will not accept," one
trader said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
