<HEADLINE> Georgia Stresses Ukraine's Role in Abkhazian Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Georgia expects
Ukraine to play a more active role in the mediation of the
Abkhazian conflict, visiting Georgian National Assembly Speaker
Zurab Zhvaniya said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After holding talks with the Ukrainian president, prime minister
and chairman of the Supreme Soviet (parliament), Zhvaniya told a
press conference that Ukraine could play a key role in solving the
Abkhazian problem.
</P>
<P>
In response, Alexander Moroz, chairman of the Supreme Soviet of
Ukraine, said the Ukranian parliament would discuss the
participation of Ukraine in the mediation of the Abkhazian dispute.
</P>
<P>
A military conflict in the western Georgian region broke out in
August 1992 when the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia declared
itself a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze and
the Abkhazian leadership, Russian peacekeeping troops entered
Abkhazia in mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
Zhvaniya however told reporters that so far he was not
satisfied with the Russian mediation.
</P>
<P>
Zhvaniya arrived in Kiev on Thursday morning for a two-day
official visit. Upon his arrival, he said that Georgia regards
Ukraine as one of the most friendly and brotherly countries.
</P>
<P>
The close ties between Georgia and Ukraine could become a model
for cooperation among the members of the Commonwealth of
Independent States, he added. 
</P>
