<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Suburbs Gain Economic Importance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 13 (Xinhua) -- The suburban areas of
Shanghai, China's largest manufacturing center, contributed a
quarter of the city's gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997, according to
the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The GDP (the value of goods and services produced) of suburban
Shanghai surged 18.8 percent to 95.84 billion yuan last year,
about 28.5 percent of the city's total. The ratio was 1.2
percentage points higher than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Economists note that the manufacturing industry of Shanghai,
China's largest economic center, is moving to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,875 enterprises have moved to the nine industrial
zones in the suburban districts and counties, while
overseas-funded enterprises have begun investing heavily in the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's suburbs had 8,633 overseas-funded enterprises at the
end of last year. The 5,780 operational ones registered a total
turnover of 42.8 billion yuan and earned 5.35 billion US dollars
from exports last year.
</P>
<P>
Vice Mayor Feng Guoqin said that township-run enterprises in
Shanghai, which used to be widely scattered, are pursuing an
economy of scale to increase efficiency. Currently 159 enterprise
groups have been formed, with their combined industrial output
value and profit accounting for 15 and 27.7 percent, respectively,
of the total of the suburban areas.
</P>
<P>
Suburban industries have become the largest single driving
force behind Shanghai's industrial growth, Feng said, adding that
the city's suburbs had an industrial output value of 54.7 billion
yuan last year, about 43 percent of the city's total, three
percentage points higher than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The service sector, such as tourism, real estate and
commerce, has recorded considerable growth in the suburban
areas in recent years, according to Feng.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that last year the service sector's
added value soared 22.6 percent to 33.5 billion yuan, about
28.5 percent of Shanghai's total.
</P>
<P>
The non-state sector has also shifted its focus to the suburbs
because of economic potential. Currently there are 81,000
individually-run industrial and commercial businesses and 61,600
private enterprises in suburban Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Last year the suburban areas scored a total output value of
7.58 billion yuan, up 4.2 percent year-on-year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
