<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quality Controls Get Acceptance Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- chinese quality system
certificates are now accepted worldwide following the signing of a
multilateral recognition agreement, according to today's "China
Daily".
</P>
<P>
The Multilateral Recognition Agreement on Quality System
Certificates, a creation of the five-year-old International
Accreditation Forum, was signed in Guangzhou last month by 16
accreditation bodies representing 17 countries, including the
United States, Germany, France, Japan and Australia, said Zhu
Mingxian, deputy director of the State Bureau of Technical
Supervision.
</P>
<P>
"The China National Accreditation Council for Registrars
(CNACR) was among the first signatories as the only national
accreditation body from a developing country," said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Quality system registration has been growing rapidly since the
issue of the first edition of ISO9000 international standards in
1987.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the International Accreditation Forum show that
about 100 countries and regions have adopted the ISO9000
standards, and quality system certificates issued by accredited
quality system registrars are playing an important role in
promoting international trade.
</P>
<P>
Quality system registration has grown since it was introduced
to China in 1992.
</P>
<P>
by the end of last year, 4,042 certificates bearing the
national accreditation marks had been issued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's Jiangsu Improving Export-Oriented Economic Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
is working to improve its export-oriented economic structure and
will raise the proportion of the export-oriented economy in the
province's gross economic product from the present 25 percent to
over 30 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, the economically-developed province has
witnessed a fast growth of its export-oriented economy and has
been on top among all provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions in terms of export, the use of overseas funds and
international economic and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Provincial leaders said that the adjusting efforts are aimed at
making the province adapted to demand and economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
The province will improve its current foreign trade structure
and expand the technological and service trade.
</P>
<P>
In the years to come, the province will export more commodities
with high technological contents. Manufactured goods will make up
95 percent of the province's entire exports.
</P>
<P>
The province will concentrate efforts on exploring markets in
Africa, Central and South Americas, Southeast Asia, Eastern
Europe, and Russia while expanding markets in Hong Kong, Japan,
the United States and the European Union
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the province will widely spread ISO
(International Standardization Organization) 9000 quality control
and quality guarantee standards and will make 75 percent of the
province's major exported commodities produced in accordance with
international standards in two or three years.
</P>
<P>
The province will also improve overseas investment structure
and try flexible ways to attract more overseas investment. 
</P>
