<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Iraq Has No Choice But to Comply With UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Thursday warned that there is no choice for
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein but to abide by U.N. resolutions on
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"Saddam does not have a menu of choices," she told a hearing of
the House International Relations Committee. "He has one: Iraq
must comply with the (Security) Council resolutions and provide
U.N. inspectors with the unfettered access they need to do their
job."
</P>
<P>
The United States dismissed a Russian plan made public by Iraq
Wednesday for limited access to eight presidential sites to be
carried out not by regular U.N. inspectors but by a special
mission under the authority of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"There is still time for a diplomatic solution, but if Iraq's
behavior does not change very soon, we will have no choice but to
take strong measures -- not pinpricks, but substantial strikes,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright also told the House committee that the United States
would check a report, published in the Washington Post Thursday,
that alleged Russia had negotiated to sell Iraq highly-sensitive,
dual-use technology that could be used to produce biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We'll certainly follow it, as we see it as a very serious
issue," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia has been working to strengthen its export controls and
we have been encouraging the Russians to investigate incidents as
we have become aware of them."
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen urged the United Nations to
make an investigation to find whether there is any evidence for
that contract.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have any means of verifying that. That's something
that the U.N. will have to determine, and hopefully the Russian
authorities will be very forthcoming on this issue," he told ABC
in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But Russia dismissed the report as "crude inventions."
</P>
<P>
"We decisively deny these crude inventions," Russia's Foreign
Ministry said Thursday. "Russia has never made any deals with Iraq
that would violate international sanctions, moreover deals
involving supplies of banned technologies."
</P>
<P>
More U.S. fighters and bombers took off from their domestic
bases for the Gulf Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Six F-16 fighter jets have left there Shaw Air Force Base,
South Carolina. And six B-52 bombers and one B-1 bomber are
scheduled to leave later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Six F-117A stealth fighters are expected to depart Friday.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the warplanes along with some 23 refueling
tankers and other support planes will boost the total of U.S.
attack and support aircraft in the region to about 350.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,200 Marines aboard ship are expected to arrive in
the Gulf at the weekend. And 3,000 Army troops are expected to be
flown to Kuwait within days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
