<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solana Sees Big Troop Withdrawal from Bosnia This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) can begin a significant military withdrawal
from Bosnia with the political situation there improving, NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"My recommendation would be to start now with a force a little
bit lower than the 35,000 we have now, so that by the end of the
year we could start a drawdown of a significant nature," Solana
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR), currently deployed in
Bosnia, is expected to conclude its mission by the end of June.
The U.S. and its NATO allies are planning for a replacement force.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration decided at the end of last year to
continue to deploy ground troops in Bosnia because of the fear
that a total withdrawal would lead to a resumption of warfare in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Giving an optimistic assessment of the situation in Bosnia,
Solana said that the improving political picture and the prospect
of presidential elections in September open the way to easing the
demand for peacekeeping forces in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Recent arrests by SFOR of indicted war criminals, unifying
steps such as the establishment of a Bosnian currency and auto
license plates, and successful regional elections point to an
improving picture, Solana said.
</P>
<P>
However, Solana said that problems persist in Bosnia.
Geographic pockets remain hotly disputed between Serbian, Muslim
and Croatian ethnic groups and the return of refugees is occurring
in only a handful of communities.
</P>
<P>
Solana, who is in Washington to brief lawmakers on expansion of
the alliance, said that the share of the U.S. troops in the
multi-national force in Bosnia could be reduced to 22 percent from
25 percent beginning this year with the gradual drawdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
