<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Sticks to Russian-French Initiative, FM Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf here Thursday night said that Iraq still stuck to
the Russian-French initiative which suggests opening eight
presidential sites to international arms inspectors appointed by
the U.N. Secretary General.
</P>
<P>
Iraq thought that the joint initiative was the best way to end
the current Iraqi-U.N. standoff and it now had no other plans,
said Sahhaf, who arrived here from Cairo on a three-day official
visit as part of his regional tour to rally support to fend off a
possible military attack by the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We support the Russian-French initiative," he said while
arriving at the Amman Queen Ali International Airport.
</P>
<P>
"This is not only Russia's and France's position. It reflects
the positions of all," added Sahhaf.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the United States' immediate rejection of his
proposal, the foreign minister said that Iraq would insist on
such a proposal and expected the U.N. Security Council to act in
accordance with the U.N. charters to help find a peaceful solution
to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"If they do like this, we will cooperate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the U.S. threat to carry out military action
against Iraq, Sahhaf said that Iraq knew that any war would
inflict damage on it, but the country was "not ready to put itself
under U.S. occupation yet."
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf added that Iraq would not submit to the U.S. military
threats as well as any pressure from it, as his country had to
safeguard its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. insisted that Iraq open all the suspected sites with
no preconditions, otherwise it would use military force to compel
it to do so.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf called it as "allegations" when referring to the U.S.
accusation that Iraq had mass-destruction weapons on its
presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. was using the U.N. to make trouble with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"When we say anything about the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM), it is not about the UNSCOM, it is about the
United States' allegations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Upon Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the U.N. Security
Council imposed economic sanctions on this country. Only when the
U.N. weapon inspectors certifies that all the mass-destruction
weapons are dismantled in Iraq, can the sanctions be
lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980213.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Invites Iraq to Discuss Oil-for-Food Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan Thursday formally invited Iraq to send a delegation to the
U.N. headquarters in New York to hold discussions on the
Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Annan's invitation has been sent to Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said in his invitation that he has noticed the
Iraqi complaint about his proposal after he submitted it to the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Annan proposed earlier this month to increase the amount of
oil Iraq can sell under the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal to 5.2
billion U.S. dollars over six months from original 2 billion
dollars to alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq complained that Annan's proposal would weaken
Iraq's call for the lifting of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq and
insisted that Iraq should have the right to decide on how to
distribute food and medicine purchased with its own fund.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said if the Security Council approved his
proposal, he would suggest that Iraq and the U.N. hold new
negotiations in New York to reach necessary agreement so that
Iraq could prepare and submit its food and medicine distribution
plan.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under the U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait. Under the oil-for-food deal, it is allowed to export 2
billion dollars of oil over a six month period to buy food,
medicine and other humanitarian goods for its people.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can not be lifted unless U.N. weapons inspectors
certify that Iraq has eliminated all its weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
