<HEADLINE> Iraqi Foreign Minister to Visit Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad
Saeed el-Sahhaf will visit Lebanon Saturday to explain Iraq's
stance on the crisis over arms inspection, the local radio Voice
of the People reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
El-Sahhaf will hold talks with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
and deliver him a message from Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, the
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet with Lebanese Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri,
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon will be the last leg of el-Sahhaf's current tour of
Arab states, which has taken him to Syria, Egypt and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
He is rallying support from Arab countries for Iraq's stand on
the arms inspections by the United Nations and the efforts to
thwart a possible attack on Iraq by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has agreed to open eight presidential compounds to arms
inspectors appointed by U.N. Secretary General. But the United
States and Britain have rejected the offer, saying that Iraq has
no right to set conditions for the arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, strengthening military force in the Gulf,
maintain that they will carry out substantial air strikes against
Iraq if it does not back down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
