<HEADLINE> New Grants Announced for Community Policing Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Government on
Thursday announced more than 64 million U.S.dollars in new grants to
hire more than 900 police officers, as part of a commitment to put
100,000 new officers on the streets by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
The Community Oriented Policing Services (COPS) grants will go
to 311 agencies in 48 states.
</P>
<P>
The COPS grants, part of the 1994 Crime Act, are in the form of
75 percent matching funds to state and local agencies, up to
75,000 over three years.
</P>
<P>
Since the passage of the act, more than 10,000 jurisdictions
have received COPS grants to add more than 71,000 officers and
deputies.
</P>
<P>
The COPS program aims at increasing the nation's police forces
by 20 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The biggest share of Thursday grants goes to New York, followed
by Florida, and Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
