<HEADLINE> Air Strike on Iraq Might Be Around Feb. 26: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Military experts Thursday
predicted a U.S.-British air strike on Iraq, once decided, might
take place around February 26 when a new moon just arrives.
</P>
<P>
They said the next new moon, on Feb. 26, creates a potential
window of opportunity for a possible U.S. air strike on Iraq as a
concealing dark sky, with little or no visible crescent, is the
best time to launch an attack.
</P>
<P>
"There are three or four nights of darkness on either side of
the new moon," said Geoff Chester, a spokesman for the U.S. Naval
Observatory. "It certainly helps to have no moon. When it's full,
it illuminates the sky."
</P>
<P>
A full moon could make Iraq's anti-aircraft artillery and
surface-to-air missiles easier find invading U.S. warplanes, the
experts said.
</P>
<P>
"The bottom line is: we are going to plan our mission in a way
that reduces our exposure to threats," an Air Force official said.
"The moon and the weather are just some of the considerations."
</P>
<P>
Weather can also play a significant role in attack planning,
especially in the Gulf region plagued by killing heat, high and
unpredictable winds and blinding sandstorms that can reduce
visibility to zero.
</P>
<P>
"Dust, sand and heat are deadly enemies to electronic equipment
like radios, computers, and the `black boxes' on aircraft and
other combat vehicles," said an Army history of the Gulf War.
"Weather plays an uncertain hand in aerial combat." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
